[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] In the 1980s, severe austerity measures were imposed in the Socialist Republic of Romania by President Nicolae Ceaușescu in order to pay off the external debt incurred by the state in the 1970s.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Beginning in 1981, the austerity led to economic stagnation that continued all throughout the 1980s, a "*sui generis* shock therapy" which lowered the competitiveness of the Romanian economy and decreased the amount of exports.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Between 1950 and 1975, Romania's economy grew at one of the fastest rates in the world and in the 1960s and early 1970s, Ceaușescu was considered one of the "enlightened" Eastern European leaders.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Through his domestic policies, he tried in the late 1960s to get the support of the people, as he increased wages, reformed the pension system and encouraged consumption by decreasing the prices of consumer goods.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] The infant mortality rate plummeted from 139 per 1,000 during the interwar period to 35 in the 1970's.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] During the interwar period half the population was illiterate but under the communist government illiteracy was eradicated.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] The population became urbanized, women's rights greatly improved, life expectancy grew, among many other achievements.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] However, as the economy continued to grow in the 1970s, much of the growth was achieved through investment in heavy industry (34.1% of the GDP in the 1971–1975 five-year plan) rather than consumption.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Some industries, such as petrochemicals and steel, had a production capacity higher than demand in the local and the available external markets, resulting in underused capacities.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Overall, the economy suffered from the combination of productive and inefficient units, as well as the falsification of statistics and large inventories of unsold production.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] The Romanian economy had a strong bias toward large enterprises: 87% of all industrial workers and 85% of industrial output were in enterprises having more than 1,000 employees, leading to a lack of flexibility of the economy.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] The growth was, according to Daniel Dăianu, a case of immiserizing growth, as the industrialization and increased ties with market economies were rushed with a weak functional basis, by ignoring the market mechanisms.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] This kind of growth limited the potential of increasing the exports, and the hard currency for repaying the loans was obtained through cuts in the imports.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Early in the 1970s, Western countries were willing to fund Romania's acquisition of technology through loans given on political considerations.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Romania's debt to Western creditors rose from just $1.2 billion in 1971 to a peak of $13 billion in 1982.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] The 1970s energy crisis, combined with the increase in interest rates, and in the context of sluggish growth and the severe global recession of 1974, made Romania incapable of repaying its debts.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] In 1981, in order to pay its due debts, Romania requested a line of credit from the International Monetary Fund and adopted a policy of paying back all its debt.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] The decision to repay the debt has been considered irrational, as other developing countries that were hit by the same problem were able to obtain debt rescheduling or "haircuts".
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] As recommended to Romania by the IMF, imports were reduced and exports were increased.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] The effect of the cuts in imports in Romania, a net importer of food from the West, was however not correctly estimated by the foreign analysts, and led to food shortages.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Romania's record - having all of its debts to commercial banks paid off in full - has not been matched by any other heavily-indebted country in the world.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] The policy to repay - and, in multiple cases, prepay - Romania's external debt became the dominant policy in the late 1980s.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] The result was economic stagnation throughout the 1980s and - towards the end of the decade - the conditions were created for an economic crisis.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] The country's industrial capacity was eroded as equipment grew obsolete, energy intensity increased, and the standard of living deteriorated significantly.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Draconian restrictions were imposed on household energy use to ensure an adequate supply for the industry.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Convertible currency exports were promoted at all costs and imports were severely compressed.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] In 1988, real GDP contracted by 0.5%, mostly due to a decline in industrial output caused by significantly increased material costs.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Despite the 1988 decline, the net foreign balance reached its decade peak (9.5% of GDP).
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] In 1989, GDP slumped by a further 5.8% due to growing shortages and increasingly obsolete capital stock.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] By March 1989, virtually all of the external debt had been repaid.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] The entire medium- and long-term external debt was repaid.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] The lingering amount, totalling less than $500 million, consisted of short-term credits (mainly short-term export credits granted by Romania).
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] A 1989 decree legally prohibited Romanian entities from contracting external debt.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] The CIA World Factbook edition of 1990 listed Romania's external debt as "none" as of mid-1989.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Ceaușescu started an austerity program without reforming Romania's centralised and inflexible planning.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Domestic energy resources were channelled towards the inefficient production of goods intended to be exported.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Even basic necessities, such as food, heating, electricity and medical care, were rationed, and infrastructure was left to decay.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Due to the austerity programme, by 1983, the standard of living had fallen by 19-40 percent, according to IMF figures.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Starting in 1978, the government began increasing the prices of goods and services that had been stable until then: included in the first wave of price increases were food, services, public transportation, clothing, wood and wood products.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] In 1979, a second wave of price increases began, for energy: prices for petrol, natural gas and electricity were increased.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Throughout 1982, prices were increased again; initially, the plan was to have just one large increase in basic goods, but eventually, the decision taken was to increase prices gradually, for all products.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Just for the year 1982, the increase reached 35%.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Not only was energy usage restricted, but its price was increased as well: electricity was raised by 30% and natural gas by 150%.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] On October 7/8, 1982, the Central Committee approved a law on the participation of workers in the investment fund of state-owned companies.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Through this act, the workers were given the "right" (in practice, it was mandatory) to invest their money and become, theoretically, co-owners of the company.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] In practice, it meant a reduction in wages for workers, with part of their earnings given to company investment funds.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] In December 1982, a new reform of the salaries system was introduced: part of the wages were to be paid to the workers only if the company achieved its goals.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] This part was initially 24% and later increased to 27%.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] The goals were often not achieved, so de facto this meant a decrease in wages.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Real incomes began to shrink not only due to inflation, but also due to the lack of availability of certain products, while the flourishing black market priced out most people.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] According to Vlad Georgescu, the state appeared to have given up its social functions, as social spending declined throughout the 1980s.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Between 1980 and 1985, cuts were made by the state in its housing expenditure (37%), healthcare (17%) and education, culture and science (53%), according to data provided to the Comecon.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] The healthcare cuts led to an increase in infant mortality rates (one of the highest in Europe) and high AIDS prevalence, the disease being transmitted through the reuse of hypodermic needles in hospitals.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] A referendum on the military was held on 23 November 1986 to reduce the size of the army and to cut military spending by 5%.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] The cuts did not affect the building of the People's House, a massive administrative building in the new Bucharest Civic Centre.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Romania's agriculture had been ignored as the government focused on industrialisation: the highly inefficient agriculture sector employed more than 30% of the working force, but received little and mismanaged investment.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Despite this, Romania's agriculture still lacked sufficient labour, the state solving the issue by taking each year millions of school children and university students (2.5 million in 1981, 2 million in 1982) to contribute to the harvest or whatever work was needed in the fields.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Romania began to suffer chronic food shortages and despite the attempts of the government to solve the problem, it persisted throughout the 1980s.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Beginning in 1983, the collective farms and individual peasants had to deliver produce to the state (something that had been previously abolished in 1956) and, when selling their products in farmers' markets, they had to adhere to strictly enforced price ceilings.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] In 1981, a rationing system for basic foodstuffs was started for bread, milk, cooking oil, sugar, and meat.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Rationing of some foodstuffs, such as bread, flour, sugar and milk, was only outside the capital, Bucharest being excepted from it.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] At Ceaușescu's initiative, a "Rational Eating Programme" began, being a "scientific plan" for limiting the calorie intake for the Romanians, claiming that the Romanians were eating too much.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] It tried to reduce the calorie intake by 9-15 percent to 2,800-3,000 calories per day.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] In December 1983, a new dietary programme for 1984 set even lower allowances.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Electricity and district heating were often stopped in order to save energy, leading to unbearable winters.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Availability of hot water was also restricted to one day per week in most apartments.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Unannounced power cuts affected even hospitals' regular functioning: for instance, in the winter of 1983, dozens of babies in neonatal intensive care units died due to the power cuts to the incubators.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Street lighting was generally reduced to a bare minimum, and often turned off.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] Petrol was rationed; private car owners were allowed to buy only 30 litres (7.9 US gallons) of petrol per month and private driving bans were regularly imposed.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] In order to save fuel, the media even appealed to peasants to replace mechanical work with manual work, using carts and horses instead of trucks and tractors.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] In 1985, Ceaușescu shut down all regional radio stations and limited television to a single channel broadcasting only two to three hours a day, in both cases to conserve energy.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] The economic austerity, along with political repression, were the main reasons behind the protests and revolution of 1989.
[src:austerity/1980s-austerity-policy-in-romania] His politics isolated him not only from the people, but also from the party (as seen by the Letter of the Six in March 1989) and the military.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The **1998–2002 Argentine great depression** was an economic depression in Argentina, which began in the third quarter of 1998 and lasted until the second quarter of 2002.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] It followed fifteen years of stagnation and a brief period of free-market reforms.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The depression, which began after the Russian and Brazilian financial crises, caused widespread unemployment, riots, the fall of the government, a default on the country's foreign debt, the rise of alternative currencies and the end of the peso's fixed exchange rate to the US dollar.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The economy shrank by 28 per cent from 1998 to 2002.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] In terms of income, over 50 per cent of Argentines lived below the official poverty line and 25 per cent were indigent (their basic needs were unmet); seven out of ten Argentine children were poor at the depth of the crisis in 2002.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] By the first half of 2003, GDP growth had returned, surprising economists and the business media, and the economy grew by an average of 9% for five years.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Bondholders who participated in the restructuring have been paid punctually and have seen the value of their bonds rise.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Argentina repaid its International Monetary Fund loans in full in 2006, but had a long dispute with the 7% of bond-holders left.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] In April 2016 Argentina came out of the default when the new government decided to repay the country's debt, paying the full amount to the vulture/hedge funds.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Argentina's many years of military dictatorship (alternating with weak, short-lived democratic governments) had already caused significant economic problems prior to the 2001 crisis, particularly during the self-styled National Reorganization Process in power from 1976 to 1983.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] A right-wing executive, José Alfredo Martínez de Hoz, was appointed Economy Minister at the outset of the dictatorship, and a neoliberal economic platform centered around anti-labour, monetarist policies of financial liberalization was introduced.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Budget deficits jumped to 15% of GDP as the country went into debt for the state takeover of over $15 billion in private debts as well as unfinished projects, higher defense spending, and the Falklands War.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Democracy was restored in 1983 with the election of President Raúl Alfonsín.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The new government intended to stabilize the economy and in 1985 introduced austerity measures and a new currency, the Argentine austral, the first of its kind without *peso* in its name.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Fresh loans were required to service the $5 billion in annual interest charges, however, and when commodity prices collapsed in 1986, the state became unable to service this debt.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] During the Alfonsin administration, unemployment did not substantially increase, but real wages fell by almost half to the lowest level in fifty years.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Prices for state-run utilities, telephone service, and gas increased substantially.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Confidence in the plan, however, collapsed in late 1987, and inflation, which had already averaged 10% per month (220% per year) from 1975 to 1988, spiraled out of control.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Inflation reached 200% for the month in July 1989, peaking at 5000% for the year.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Amid riots, Alfonsín resigned five months before the end of his term; Carlos Menem took office in July.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] After a second bout of hyperinflation, Domingo Cavallo was appointed Minister of the Economy in January 1991.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] On 1 April, he fixed the value of the austral at 10,000 per US dollar.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Australs could be freely converted to dollars at banks.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The Central Bank of Argentina had to keep its US dollar foreign-exchange reserves at the same level as the cash in circulation.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The initial aim of such measures was to ensure the acceptance of domestic currency because after the 1989 and 1990 hyperinflation, Argentines had started to demand payment in US dollars.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] This regime was later modified by a law (*Ley de Convertibilidad*) that restored the Argentine peso as the national currency.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The convertibility law reduced inflation sharply, preserving the value of the currency.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] That raised the quality of life for many citizens, who could again afford to travel abroad, buy imported goods or ask for credit in dollars at traditional interest rates.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The fixed exchange rate reduced the cost of imports, which produced a flight of dollars from the country and a massive loss of industrial infrastructure and employment in industry.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Argentina, however, still had external public debt that it needed to roll over.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Government spending remained too high, and corruption was rampant .
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Argentina's public debt grew enormously during the 1990s without showing that it could service the debt.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The IMF kept lending money to Argentina and extending its payment schedules.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Reports indicate that tax evasion and money transfers to offshore banks played a role in capital outflows.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] A congressional committee started investigations in 2001 over accusations that Central Bank Governor Pedro Pou, a prominent advocate of dollarization, and members of the board of directors had overlooked money laundering within Argentina's financial system.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Clearstream was accused of being instrumental in this process.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Other Latin American countries, including Mexico and Brazil (both important trade partners for Argentina) faced economic crises of their own, leading to mistrust of the regional economy.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The influx of foreign currency provided by the privatization of state companies had ended.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] After 1999, Argentine exports were harmed by the devaluation of the Brazilian real against the dollar.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] A considerable international revaluation of the dollar directly weakened the peso relative to Argentina's trading partners: Brazil (30% of total trade flows) and the eurozone (23% of total trade flows).
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] After having grown by over 50% from 1990 to 1998, Argentina's GDP declined by 3% in 1999 and the country entered what became a three-year-long recession.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] President Fernando de la Rúa was elected in 1999 on a reform platform that nevertheless sought to maintain the peso's parity with the dollar.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] He inherited a country with high unemployment (15%), lingering recession, and continued high levels of borrowing.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] In 1999, economic stability became economic stagnation (even deflation at times), and the economic measures taken did nothing to avert it.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The government continued its predecessor's economic policies.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Devaluing the peso by abandoning the exchange peg was considered political suicide and a recipe for economic disaster.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] By the end of the century, complementary currencies had emerged.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The large amounts of borrowing by Menem.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] An increase in debt from reduced tax revenues.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The 2002 crisis of the Argentine peso, however, shows that even a currency board arrangement cannot be completely safe from a possible collapse.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] When the peso was first linked to the U.S. dollar at parity in February 1991 under the Convertibility Law, initial economic effects were quite positive: Argentina's chronic inflation was curtailed dramatically and foreign investment began to pour in, leading to an economic boom.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Over time, however, the peso appreciated against the majority of currencies as the U.S. dollar became increasingly stronger in the second half of the 1990s.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] A strong peso hurt exports from Argentina and caused a protracted economic downturn that eventually led to the abandonment of the peso-dollar parity in 2002.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] This change, in turn, caused severe economic and political distress in the country.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The unemployment rate rose above 20 per cent and inflation reached a monthly rate of about 20 per cent in April 2002.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] In contrast, Hong Kong was able to successfully defend its currency board arrangement during the Asian financial crisis, a major stress test for the arrangement.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Contagion from the financial crises in Russia and Brazil.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] While the currency crisis is over, the debt problem has not been completely resolved.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The government of Argentina ceased all debt payments in December 2001 in the wake of persistent recession and rising social and political unrest.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] In 2004, the Argentine government made a 'final' offer amounting to a 75 per cent reduction in the net present value of the debt.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Foreign bondholders rejected this offer and asked for an improved offer.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] In early 2005, bondholders finally agreed to the restructuring, under which they took a cut of about 70 per cent on the value of their bond holdings.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] While the provinces of Argentina had always issued complementary currency in the form of bonds and drafts to manage shortages of cash, the scale of such borrowing reached unprecedented levels during this period.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] They became called "quasi-currencies", the strongest of them being Buenos Aires's Patacón.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The national government issued its own quasi-currency, the LECOP.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The Crédito also emerged in 1995 as a complementary currency for facilitating barter.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Some versions of Crédito were unique for being demurrage currency.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] When a short boom in the early 1990s of portfolio investment from abroad ended in 1995, Argentina became reliant on the IMF to provide the country with low-interest access to credit and to guide its economic reforms.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] When the recession began in 1999, the national deficit widened to 2.5% of GDP, and its external debt surpassed 50% of GDP.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Seeing the levels as excessive, the IMF advised the government to balance its budget by implementing austerity measures to sustain investor confidence.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The De la Rúa administration implemented $1.4 billion in cuts in its first weeks in office in late 1999.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] In June 2000, with unemployment at 14% and projections of 3.5% GDP for the year, austerity was furthered by $938 million in spending cuts and $2 billion in tax increases.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] GDP growth projections proved to be overly optimistic (instead of growing, real GDP shrank 0.8%), and lagging tax receipts prompted the government to freeze spending and cut retirement benefits again.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] In early November, Standard & Poor's placed Argentina on a credit watch, and a treasury bill auction required paying 16% interest (up from 9% in July, the second-highest rate of any country in South America at the time.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Rising bond yields forced the country to turn to major international lenders, such as the IMF, the World Bank, and the US Treasury, which would lend to the government below market rates if it complied with conditions.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Several more rounds of belt-tightening followed.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] José Luis Machinea resigned in March 2001.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] He was replaced with Ricardo López Murphy, who lasted less than three weeks in office before being replaced with Cavallo.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Standard and Poor's cut the credit rating of the country's bonds to B− in July 2001.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Cavallo reacted by offering bondholders a swap: longer-term, higher-interest bonds would be exchanged for bonds due in 2010.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] That further depressed the weakened economy, the unemployment rate rose to 16.4% in August 2001 up from a 14.7% a month earlier, and it reached 20% by December.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Public discontent with the economic conditions was expressed in the nationwide election.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] De la Rúa's alliance lost its majority in both chambers of Congress.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Over 20% of voters chose to give blank or defaced ballots rather than indicate support of any candidate.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The crisis intensified when, on 5 December 2001, the IMF refused to release a US$1.3 billion tranche of its loan, citing the failure of the Argentine government to reach its budget deficit targets, and it demanded budget cuts, 10% of the federal budget.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] On 4 December, Argentine bond yields stood at 34% over U.S. treasury bonds, and, by 11 December, the spread jumped to 42%.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] By the end of November 2001, people began withdrawing large sums of dollars from their bank accounts, turning pesos into dollars, and sending them abroad, which caused a bank run.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] On 2 December, the government enacted measures, informally known as the *corralito*, which allowed for only minor sums of cash to be withdrawn, initially $250 a week.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The bank withdrawal freeze led to widespread protests, particularly in Buenos Aires.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] They engaged in protests known as *cacerolazo* (banging pots and pans).
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Initially peaceful, these demonstrations later involved damage to property, including banks and foreign-owned companies, particularly those from the United States and Europe.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Confrontations between the police and citizens became common, and fires were set on Buenos Aires avenues.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] De la Rúa declared a state of emergency, but the situation worsened, precipitating the violent protests of 20 and 21 December 2001 in Plaza de Mayo, where clashes between demonstrators and the police ended up with several people dead and precipitated the fall of the government.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] De la Rúa eventually fled the Casa Rosada in a helicopter on 21 December.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Following the presidential succession procedures established in the Constitution of Argentina, the Senate chairman was next in the line of succession in the absence of the president and the vice-president.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Accordingly, Ramón Puerta took office as a caretaker head of state, and the Legislative Assembly (a joint session of both chambers of Congress) was convened.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Adolfo Rodríguez Saá, the governor of San Luis Province, was eventually appointed as the new interim president.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] During the last week of 2001, the administration defaulted on the larger part of the public debt, US$132 billion, a seventh of all the money borrowed by the Third World.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Politically, the most heated debate involved the date of the following elections.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Proposals ranged from March 2002 to October 2003, the end of De la Rúa's term.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Rodríguez Saá's economic team came up with a scheme designed to preserve the convertibility regime, dubbed the "Third Currency" Plan.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] It consisted of creating a new, non-convertible currency, the *Argentino*, that would coexist with convertible pesos and US dollars.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] It would circulate as cash, or but not in checks, promissory notes, or other instruments, which could be denominated in pesos or dollars.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] It would be partially guaranteed with federally managed land to counterbalance inflationary tendencies.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Argentines having legal status would be used to redeem all complementary currency already in circulation; their acceptance as a means of payment was quite uneven.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] It was hoped that convertibility would restore public confidence, and the non-convertible nature of this currency would allow for a measure of fiscal flexibility (unthinkable with pesos) to ameliorate the crippling recession.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Critics called the plan merely a "controlled devaluation" but its advocates countered that since controlling a devaluation is perhaps its thorniest issue, that criticism was a praise in disguise.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The plan had enthusiastic supporters among mainstream economists (the most well-known being perhaps Martín Redrado, a former Banco Central de la República Argentina president) citing technical arguments.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] However, it was not implemented because the Rodríguez Saá government lacked the required political support.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Rodriguez Saá lost the support of his own Justicialist Party and resigned before the end of the year.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The Legislative Assembly convened again, appointing Peronist Senator Eduardo Duhalde of Buenos Aires Province, who had been the runner-up in the 1999 race for the presidency.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] In January 2002, after much deliberation, Duhalde abandoned the fixed exchange rate that had been in place for ten years.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] In a matter of days, the peso lost a large part of its value in the unregulated market.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] A provisional "official" exchange rate was set at 1.4 pesos per US dollar.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] In addition to the *corralito*, the Ministry of Economy dictated the *pesificación*; all bank accounts denominated in dollars would be converted to pesos at an official rate.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Deposits would be converted at 1.40 ARS per dollar and debt was converted on 1 to 1 basis.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The exchange rate spiked as depositors converted their peso deposits back into US dollars.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] By October 2002, depositors who withdraw lost 50% of their value in dollars.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] That angered most savings holders and attempts were made to declare it unconstitutional.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] After a few months, the exchange rate was mostly a floating exchange rate.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The peso further depreciated, which prompted increased inflation.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Argentina depended heavily on imports but then could not replace them locally.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Inflation and unemployment worsened during 2002.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The exchange rate had reached nearly 4 pesos per dollar, and the accumulated inflation since the devaluation was about 80%, considerably less than predicted by most orthodox economists.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The quality of life of the average Argentine was lowered proportionally.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Many businesses closed or went bankrupt, many imported products became virtually inaccessible, and salaries were left as they were before the crisis.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Since the supply of pesos did not meet the demand for cash (even after the devaluation), complementary currencies kept circulating alongside them.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Fears of hyperinflation as a consequence of devaluation quickly eroded their attractiveness.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Their acceptability now ultimately depended on the state's irregular willingness to take them as payment of taxes and other charges.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] While the regional currency was frequently accepted at the same value as the peso, Entre Ríos Province's *Federal* fared among the worst, discounted by an average 30% as even the provincial government that had issued them was reluctant to accept them.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] There were also frequent rumors that the first state would banish complementary currency overnight, leaving their holders with useless printed paper.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Aerolíneas Argentinas was one of the most affected Argentine companies, canceling all international flights for various days in 2002.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The airline came close to bankruptcy but survived.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Several thousand homeless and jobless Argentines found work as *cartoneros*, cardboard collectors.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] An estimate in 2003 had 30,000 to 40,000 people scavenging the streets for cardboard to sell to recycling plants.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Such desperate measures were common because of the unemployment rate, nearly 25%.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Argentine agricultural products were rejected in some international markets for fear that they might have been damaged by the chaos.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The US Department of Agriculture put restrictions on Argentine food and drug exports.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Duhalde eventually stabilised the situation somewhat and called for elections.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] On 25 May 2003, Néstor Kirchner took office as the new president.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Kirchner kept Duhalde's Minister of Economy, Roberto Lavagna.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Lavagna, a respected economist with centrist views, showed a considerable aptitude at managing the crisis, with the help of heterodox measures.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The economic outlook was completely different from that of the 1990s.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The devalued peso made Argentine exports cheap and competitive abroad and discouraged imports.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] In addition, the high price of soybeans in the international market produced massive amounts of foreign currency; China became a major buyer of Argentina's soy products.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The government encouraged import substitution and accessible credit for businesses, staged an aggressive plan to improve tax collection, and allocated large sums for social welfare but controlled expenditure in other fields.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The peso slowly rose, reaching a 3-to-1 rate to the dollar.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Agricultural exports grew and tourism returned.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The huge trade surplus ultimately caused such an inflow of dollars that the government was forced to begin intervening to keep the peso from rising further, which would have adversely affected budget balances by limiting export tax revenues and discouraged further reindustrialisation.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The central bank started rebuilding its dollar reserves.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] By December 2005, foreign currency reserves had reached $28 billion (they were later reduced by the payment of the full debt to the IMF in January 2006 (2006-01)).
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The downside of this reserve accumulation strategy is that US dollars had to be bought with freshly issued pesos, which risked inflation.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The Central Bank sterilized its purchases by buying Treasury letters.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] In this way the exchange rate stabilised to about 3:1.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The government set up controls and restrictions aimed at keeping short-term speculative investment from destabilising financial markets.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The country faced a potential debt crisis in late July 2014, when a New York judge ordered Argentina to pay hedge funds the full interest on bonds it had swapped at a discount rate during 2002.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] If the judgement proceeded, Argentina argued, the country would become insolvent and have a second debt default.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Argentina's recovery suffered a minor setback in 2004, when rising industrial demand caused a short-lived energy crisis.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Though wages averaged a 17% annual increase from 2002 to 2008, and rising 25% in the year to May 2008, inflation ate away at the increases: 12.5% in 2005; 10% in 2006; nearly 15% in 2007, and over 20% during 2008.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The government was accused of manipulating inflation statistics, and *The Economist* began to turn to private sources instead.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The surveying volume prompted the government to increase export tariffs and to pressure retailers into one price freeze after another in a bid to stabilize prices but with little effect.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] While unemployment has been considerably reduced (it has hovered around 7% since 2011), Argentina has so far failed to reach an equitable distribution of income.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Nevertheless, economic recovery after 2002 was accompanied by significant improvements in income distribution: in 2002, the richest 10% absorbed 40% of all income, compared to 1.1% for the poorest 10% (36 times); but by 2013, the former received 27.6% of income, and the latter, 2% (14 times).
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] That level of inequality compares favorably to levels in most of Latin America and, in recent years, the United States as well.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Living standards recovered significantly after growth resumed in 2003.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Even using private inflation estimates, real wages rose by around 72% from their low point, in 2003, to 2013.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Argentina's domestic new auto market recovered especially quickly from a low of 83,000 in 2002 (a fifth the levels of the late 1990s) to a record 964,000 in 2013.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] During the economic collapse, many business owners and foreign investors sent their money overseas.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] As a result, many small and medium enterprises closed for lack of capital.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The majority of their workers, faced with a sudden loss of employment and no source of income, decided to reopen the closed facilities on their own as self-managed cooperatives.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Worker cooperatives include the factory Zanon (FaSinPat), the four-star Hotel Bauen, the suit factory Brukman, and the printing press Chilavert.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] In some cases, former owners sent police to remove workers from the workplaces; that was sometimes successful but in other cases, workers defended occupied workplaces against the state, the police, and the bosses.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] A survey by an Buenos Aires newspaper found that around a third of the population had participated in general assemblies.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The assemblies used to take place in street corners and public spaces, and they generally discussed ways of helping each other in the face of eviction, or organizing around issues such as health care, collective food buying, or food distribution programs.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Some created new structures of health care and schooling.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Neighborhood assemblies met once a week in a large assembly to discuss issues that affected the larger community.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] In 2004, *The Take*, a documentary, was released on the assemblies.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Although GDP grew consistently and quickly after 2003, it did not reach the levels of 1998, the last year before the crisis, until late 2004.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Other macroeconomic indicators followed suit.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] A study by Equis, an independent counseling organization, found out that two measures of economic inequality, the Gini coefficient and the wealth gap between the 10% poorest and the 10% richest among the population, grew continuously from 2001 to March 2005.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Similar statistics are available from the World Bank.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] When the default was declared in 2002, foreign investment stopped, and capital flow ceased almost completely and immediately.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The government faced severe challenges in trying to refinance its debt.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The government reached an agreement in 2005 by which 76% of the defaulted bonds were exchanged for other bonds at a nominal value of 25 to 35% of the original and at longer terms.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] A second debt restructuring in 2010 brought the percentage of bonds out of default to 93%, but some creditors have still not been paid.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Foreign currency denominated debt thus fell as a percentage of GDP from 150% in 2003 to 8.3% in 2013.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The IMF accepted no discounts in its part of the Argentine debt.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Some payments were refinanced or postponed on agreement.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] However, IMF authorities at times expressed harsh criticism of the discounts and actively lobbied for the private creditors.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] In 2005, after turning its primary surplus into an actual surplus, Argentina began paying the IMF on schedule, with the intention of regaining financial independence.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] On 15 December 2005, following a similar action by Brazil, Kirchner suddenly announced that Argentina would pay the whole debt to the IMF.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] The debt payments, totaling US$9.810 billion, were previously scheduled as instalments until 2008.
[src:austerity/1998-2002-argentine-great-depression] Argentina paid it with the central bank's foreign currency reserves.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The **2008–2014 Spanish financial crisis**, also known as the **Great Recession in Spain** or the **Great Spanish Depression**, began in 2008 during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] In 2012, it made Spain a late participant in the Euro area crisis when the country was unable to bail out its financial sector and had to apply for a €100 billion rescue package provided by the European Stability Mechanism (ESM).
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The main cause of Spain's crisis was the housing bubble and the accompanying unsustainably high GDP growth rate.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The ballooning tax revenues from the booming property investment and construction sectors kept the Spanish government's revenue in surplus, despite strong increases in expenditure, until 2007.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The Spanish government supported the critical development by relaxing supervision of the financial sector and thereby allowing the banks to violate International Accounting Standards Board standards.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The banks in Spain were able to hide losses and earnings volatility, mislead regulators, analysts, and investors, and thereby finance the Spanish real estate bubble.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The results of the crisis were devastating for Spain, including a strong economic downturn, a severe increase in unemployment, and bankruptcies of major companies.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Even though some fundamental problems in the Spanish economy were already evident far ahead of the crisis, Spain continued the path of unsustainable property led growth when the ruling party changed in 2004.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] In these times Spain had already a huge trade deficit, a loss of competitiveness against its main trading partners, an above-average inflation rate, house price increases, and a growing family indebtedness.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] During the third quarter of 2008 the national GDP contracted for the first time in 15 years, and, in February 2009, Spain (and other European economies) officially entered recession.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The economy contracted 3.7% in 2009 and again in 2010 by 0.1%.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] By the 1st quarter of 2012, Spain was officially in recession once again.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The Spanish government forecast a 1.7% drop for 2012.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The provision of up to €100 billion of rescue loans from eurozone funds was agreed by eurozone finance ministers on 9 June 2012.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] As of October 2012, the so-called Troika (European Commission, ECB and IMF) was in negotiations with Spain to establish an economic recovery program required for providing additional financial loans from the European Stability Mechanism (ESM).
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] In addition to applying for a €100 billion bank recapitalization package in June 2012, Spain negotiated financial support from a "Precautionary Conditioned Credit Line" (PCCL) package.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The turning point for the Spanish sovereign debt crisis occurred on 26 July 2012, when ECB President Mario Draghi said that the ECB was "ready to do whatever it takes to preserve the euro".
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Announced on 6 September 2012, the ECB's Outright Monetary Transactions (OMT) program of unlimited purchases of short-term sovereign debt put the ECB's balance sheet behind the pledge.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Speculative runs against Spanish sovereign debt were discouraged and 10-year bond yields stayed below the 6% level, approaching the 5% level by the end of 2012.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The residential real estate bubble saw real estate prices rise 200% from 1996 to 2007.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] €651 billion was the mortgage debt of Spanish families in the second quarter of 2005 (this debt continued to grow at 25% per year – 2001 through 2005, with 97% of mortgages at variable rate interest).
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] In 2004, 509,293 new properties were built in Spain and in 2005 the number of new properties built was 528,754.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] In a country with 16.5 million families, there were 22–24 million houses and 3–4 million empty houses.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] From all the houses built over the 2001–2007 period, "no less than 28%" were vacant as of late 2008.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The desire to own one's own home was encouraged by governments in the 60s and 70s, and has thus become part of the Spanish psyche.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] In addition, tax regulation encourages ownership: 15% of mortgage payments are deductible from personal income taxes.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Even more, the oldest apartments are controlled by non-inflation-adjusted rent controls and eviction is slow, therefore discouraging renting.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] When the speculative bubble popped Spain became one of the worst affected countries.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] According to Eurostat, between June 2007 and June 2008, Spain has been the European country with the sharpest plunge in construction, with actual sales down an average 25.3%.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] So far, some regions have been more affected than others (Catalonia was ahead in this regard with a 42.2% sales plunge while sparsely populated regions like Extremadura were down a mere 1.7% over the same period).
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Banks offered 40-year mortgages and, more recently, 50-year mortgages.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] While some observers suggest that a soft landing would occur, others suggest that a crash in prices is probable.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Lower home prices would allow low-income families and young people to enter the market; however, there is a strong perception that house prices never go down.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] As of August 2008, while new constructions have come virtually to a halt, prices have not had significant movements either up or downwards.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The national average price as of late 2008 is 2,095 euros/m2.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Housing prices were projected to fall another 25%.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Government protections allow banks to avoid marking-to-market to postpone losses.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] "Spanish housing prices are now falling at the fastest pace on record" dropping 15.2% over the last year.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Mortgage holders must continue to pay the debt even after a foreclosure.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Banks have begun to accept "deed-in-lieu deals" in which the debt is cancelled if the property is surrendered, allowing the bank to quickly sell and recoup a greater percentage of the loan or turn the property into a rental.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] For instance, the town of Valdeluz was constructed for 30,000 people, but had a population of only 700 people in 2011.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Ghost airports such as €1.1 billion Ciudad Real Central Airport, Castellón-Costa Azahar Airport and others were built.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Due to the lack of its own resources, Spain has to import all of its fossil fuels, which in a scenario of record prices added much pressure to the inflation rate.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Thus, in June 2008 the inflation rate reached a 13-year high of 5.00%.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] As of October 2010, the Spanish economy continued to contract, resulting in decreasing GDP and increasing inflation.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] From 2011 to 2012 alone, prices rose 3.5% as compared to 2% in the United States.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The rise in prices, combined with the recently implemented austerity measures and extremely high unemployment, are heavily impacting the livelihood of Spanish citizens.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] As the average wage decreases, the buying power of money decreases as well.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The frustration of this decreases in buying power has manifested in several, very large, worker demonstrations.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The Spanish banking system had been seen as one of the most solid and best equipped among all Western banking systems for coping with the worldwide liquidity crisis, thanks to the country's conservative banking rules and practices.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Banks are required to have high capital provisions and demand various proofs and securities from intending borrowers.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Nevertheless, this practice was greatly relaxed during the housing bubble, a trend to which the regulator (Banco de España) turned a blind eye.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] However, during the financial crisis, Spain's unusual accounting standards, intended to smooth earnings over the business cycle, misled regulators and analysts by hiding earnings volatility and losses.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The accounting technique known as "dynamic provisioning", which violated the standards set by the International Accounting Standards Board, obscured the depletion of capital reserves, giving banks a false appearance of financial health even as liquidity problems mounted.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] It was later revealed that nearly all the Spanish representatives in Congress had large investments in the housing sector, some owning up to twenty houses.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] In stark contrast to countries like Ireland, no nationalization took place.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Instead the problem was rolled over with the extension of the remaining real estate companies debts, while the central government bailed once and again banks and cajas alike.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] For more than three years, there was a steady process of bank concentration.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Spain had the densest bank office net in Europe, which led many bank employees to be dismissed.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] By contrast, bank board members have mostly kept their roles, even those in merged entities.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Golden parachutes have been prevalent: it has been speculated that this was because of the fear that laid-off senior members would talk about the sector's rampant malpractice.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] To this date, no bankers have been legally charged for having roles in this process.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] In May 2012 the credit ratings of several Spanish banks were downgraded, some to "junk" status.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The Bankia bank, the country's largest mortgage lender, was nationalized on 9 May, and on 25 May it announced that it would require a bailout of €23.5 billion to cover losses from failed mortgages.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] In addition to Spanish banks, other European banks have a sizable presence in Spain.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] German banks lead with an exposure of $146 billion.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Germany's Landesbanks entered the market during the early 2000s.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Barclays, Deutsche Bank, and ING have large Spanish units.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] On 9 June 2012 Eurozone finance ministers agreed that Spanish banks would be provided with up to €100 billion of rescue loans.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] This money was to be distributed via the Fund for Orderly Bank Restructuring, and the exact amount to be loaned would be determined after audits of the banks.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] EC President Jose Manuel Barroso and vice-president Olli Rehn welcomed the move, praising the combination of a "thorough restructuring of the banking sector", structural reforms, and fiscal consolidation; U.S.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Treasury Secretary Timothy Geithner also welcomed the move.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Bank stress tests would enable the Spanish government to make a formal request for the €100 billion credit line.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Further analysis and tests would be undertaken prior to restructuring and recapitalization over the following year.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Restrictions on the credit line exempting funds from covering "legacy assets" suggests limits to the planned banking bailouts.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] In May 2012, Spanish banks lent €1.66 trillion to the private sector and took in €896 billion.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Historically it would borrow the difference from foreign banks (i.e., interbank lending) but reduced access led to a greater reliance on ECB loans.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Spanish banks borrowed a record €376 billion (net) from the ECB in July 2012.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Depositors were fleeing Spanish banks; deposits dropped 4.7% from June to July (2012) as money was moved abroad.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] On 28 November 2012, the European Commission approved the Spanish government's plan to shrink and restructure three major Spanish banks —Bankia, NCG Banco, and Catalunya Banc — and sell a fourth, Banco de Valencia.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] This is part of a €37 billion EC bailout or restructuring approved in June 2012.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] It included loss-taking by investors of up to €10 billion, the creation of a "bad bank" to absorb up to €45 billion of failed loans, closing thousands of bank branches, and reducing staff.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] After having completed substantial improvements over the second half of the 1990s and during the 2000s, which put a few regions on the brink of full employment, Spain suffered a severe setback in October 2008, when it saw its unemployment rate surging to 1996 levels.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Between October 2007 and October 2008, Spain had its unemployment rate climb 36%, exceeding by far the unemployment surge of past economic crises like 1993.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] In particular, in October 2008, Spain suffered its worst unemployment rise ever recorded and, the country has suffered Europe's biggest unemployment crisis during the 2008 crisis.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Spain's unemployment rate hit 17.4% at the end of March 2009, with the jobless total now having doubled over the past 12 months, when two million people lost their jobs.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] In this same month, Spain had over 4 million people unemployed, By July 2009, it had shed 1.2 million jobs in one year and was to have the same number of jobless as France and Italy combined.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] By March 2012, Spain's unemployment rate reached 24.4%, twice the eurozone average.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] In 2012, unions organized a general strike to protest proposals to weaken union power, enable cuts in wages, and lower firing costs.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] By the end of 2012, Spain's unit labor costs improved.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] It narrowed the gap with Germany by 5.5% and 4.6% with respect to France.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Spain's policy of *internal devaluation* cut public sector salaries by 5% with an additional 7.1% cut consisting of a suspension of the "14-month bonus".
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Spain, as in other southern European nations, relies heavily on the inter-generational family structure for a significant portion of the social safety net.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Employment expectations should be adjusted for this cultural ethos.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The unemployment rate for the "principal breadwinner" is 12.4% less than the 25% overall rate (June 2012.) Employment is also found in the underground economy, which is estimated to be as large as 20% of the economy during the boom years.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Unemployment for those under 25 was reported to be up to 50%.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Spain's current generation is considered the most educated that the country has ever had, yet it faces the greatest rate of unemployment in Europe.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Roughly 68% of young people are willing to leave the country to search for a job, and those with college degrees are willing to settle for working at so-called minijobs for a paycheck.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The State Secretary for Unemployment states that higher education is a way for the current generation to battle this issue; however, government cuts are occurring that slash university staff salaries and increase the number of students per class.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] For those paying their own way through their studies, the tough economy has made it nearly impossible to find a job and study simultaneously.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Hopes for the future are dwindling as Spain's unemployment rate is almost as high as it was for the United States during the Great Depression.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] People are beginning to fear the transformation of this generation into one referred to as a "Lost Generation" that is constantly looking for work and whose futures are closed off from "good careers".
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The stress of unemployment has also affected personal relationships, with many young adults separating from their partners.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Youth unemployment is about double the overall rate of unemployment.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The high unemployment rate, at 56% as of June 2013, has been considered to be overstated.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Subtracting students and young mothers not looking for jobs, the actual number is closer to 22%.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Large-scale immigration continued throughout 2008 despite severe unemployment, but by 2011 the OECD confirmed that the total number of people leaving the country (Spaniards and non-Spaniards) had over taken the number of arrivals.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] There are now indications that established immigrants have begun to leave, although many that have are still retaining a household in Spain due to the poor conditions that exist in their country of origin.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] As the financial crisis was getting started in Spain, it was already underway in the United States and other western countries.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The decrease in disposable income of consumers led to a sharp decrease in Spain's tourist industry, a rarity in a country with so many coastal towns.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Indeed, the EU as a group saw a decline in tourists coming to their countries in 2008 and 2009, with −13% tourism growth in coastal Spain.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Despite its traditional popularity with Korean and Japanese tourists, the relatively expensive cost of holidaying in Spain led many to pursue "sun and beach" Mediterranean getaways in Turkey, Spain's tourism rival.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] However, Spain has also seen the largest growth in tourism since 2011 and 2012.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Its geographic advantages, the Arab Spring, and other non-economic factors are contributing to its resurgence as a tourist destination.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] While Spain's economy itself is not doing well, purchasing power parity is generally rising again.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Furthermore, violent unrest in North Africa and the Middle East is redirecting tourists towards stable countries like Spain.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Spain entered the crisis period with a relatively modest public debt of 36.2% of GDP.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] This was largely due to ballooning tax revenue from the housing bubble, which helped accommodate a decade of increased government spending without debt accumulation.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] In response to the crisis, Spain initiated an austerity program consisting primarily of tax increases.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Prime Minister Mariano Rajoy announced on 11 July 2012 €65 billion of austerity, including cuts in wages and benefits and a VAT increase from 18% to 21%.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The government eventually succeeded in reducing its budget deficit from 11.2% of GDP in 2009 to 8.5% in 2011, and it was expected to fall further to 5.4% in 2012.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] As of 15 June 2012, Spain's public debt stood at 72.1% of GDP, still less than the eurozone average of 88%.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] If Spain uses the €100 billion credit line to bail out its banks, its debt will approach 90% of GDP.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] To avoid this, the EU pledged to lend to banks directly although it then appeared that the Spanish government might have to guarantee the loans.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] In June 2012, the Spanish 10-year government bond reached 7%, 5.44% over the German 10-year bond.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] As Spanish credit default swaps (CDS) hit a record high of 633 basis points and the 10-year bond yield at 7.5% (23 July 2012), Spain's economic minister traveled to Germany to request that the ECB facilitate government bond purchases to "avoid an imminent financial collapse".
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Promised borrowing by the ECB enabled Spain's 10-year yield to stay below or close to the 6% level, settling below the 5% level in the spring of 2013.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] In 2016, public debt reached 101% of GDP.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] For the third time in 13 months, Moody's Investors Service cut Spain's rating.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] On 18 October 2011 Moody's Rating cut Spain's rating by 2 notches to A1 from Aa2 with the outlook remaining negative.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Standard and Poor's has downgraded Spain on 14 October 2011 and Fitch Ratings cut it to the same level on 7 October 2011.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] On 14 June 2012, Moody's downgraded Spain to Baa3, just one notch above "junk".
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Standard and Poor's downgraded Spain to BBB− (one notch above junk) on 11 October 2012.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] DBRS downgraded Spain to single-A, which remains higher than the major credit rating agencies.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] This rating allows the ECB to use a lower margin for banks that borrow with Spanish debt as collateral.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] After a more recent review, Moody's maintained Spain's investment-grade credit rating, removing the pressure on the country's debt.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] This decision by Moody's assured that Spanish bonds will continue to gain investor support; yields fell 5.50%, a level last seen in April 2012.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Although Moody's can still downgrade the country's ratings in the future, the decision to not downgrade will encourage the buying of Spain's bonds.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] On 9 June 2012 the Eurogroup held an emergency meeting to discuss how to inject capital into Spanish banks.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The IMF estimated the capital needs of the Spanish banks to be about 40 billion euros.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The Eurogroup announced intentions to provide up to 100 billion euro to the Fund for Orderly Bank Restructuring to the Spanish government.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The Spanish government was then expected to give the appropriate amount of money to the respective banks.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] On 21 June 2012 it was decided that 62 billion euros would be shared among the Spanish banks in need.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The European Union warned that rescued banks are subject to control and experts would meet stringent requirements.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Since then, the country's borrowing costs have reached levels deemed unsustainable in the long run, raising the prospect of a second aid program for Madrid following the 100 billion euro lifeline it obtained for its banks in June.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Spain expected the European Commission to approve the restructuring plans of the banks needing aid on 15 November 2012 and then to authorize the disbursal of the first credit line of up to 100 billion euros within three weeks after that.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] A larger economy than other countries that have received bailout packages, Spain had considerable bargaining power regarding the terms of a bailout.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Due to reforms already instituted by Spain's conservative government, less stringent austerity requirements were included than for earlier bailout packages for Ireland, Portugal, and Greece.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] As the EU's fifth-largest economy, Spain remained a large concern.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] In 2011 the conservative Mariano Rajoy took over the government, pushing out José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero and his left-wing government.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Trying to get Spain out of the highest unemployment rate in the European Union proved to be harder than expected.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The bailout for Spain was estimated to be insufficient to restore the economy.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] With a serious level of debt in the country, substantial cuts would have to be put in place to restore the economy.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Many youths are trying to find jobs abroad, creating a problem for the future domestic economy and job market.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Rajoy proposed a new budget for 2013 that would cut government spending by 8.9%.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] By April 2013, unemployment had risen to 27%, but decreased to around 15%-16.1% as of February 2018, and Spain became one of Europe's fastest-growing economies, thus demonstrating that the country was improving.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] One effect of the financial crisis is an increase in support for independence in Catalonia.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The Statute of Autonomy included a package of laws that gave more power to the region and would have recognized Catalonia as a nation, although one still within Spain.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] As with the rest of Spain, Catalonia has had high levels of unemployment.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] As many as 22% of the economically active population were unemployed, which is still lower than Spain's national jobless rate, yet higher than Madrid's.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] In 2010, Spain's Constitutional Court weakened the Statute of Autonomy for Catalonia, which further irritated Catalan secessionist organization.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The 2015 regional election was the first to produce a majority for openly separatist parties.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Prime Minister Mariano Rajoy insisted that Spain's constitution does not allow for a region to secede.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Spain's Basque Country unsuccessfully tried to get such a move approved in Parliament in 2008.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] Catalan president Artur Mas instead scheduled an independence referendum for 2014, which was downgraded to being a more informal ballot after further intervention by the Constitutional Court.
[src:austerity/2008-2014-spanish-financial-crisis] The dispute remained unresolved as of March 2015.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] A major worldwide financial crisis centered in the United States took place in 2008.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The causes included excessive speculation on property values by both homeowners and financial institutions, leading to the 2000s United States housing bubble.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This was exacerbated by predatory lending for subprime mortgages and by deficiencies in regulation.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Cash out refinancings had fueled an increase in consumption that could no longer be sustained when home prices declined.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The first phase of the crisis was the subprime mortgage crisis, which began in early 2007, as mortgage-backed securities (MBS) tied to U.S. real estate, and a vast web of derivatives linked to those MBS collapsed in value.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] A liquidity crisis spread to global institutions by mid-2007 and climaxed with the bankruptcy of Lehman Brothers in September 2008, which triggered a stock market crash and bank runs in several countries.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The crisis exacerbated the Great Recession, a global recession that began in late-2007, as well as the United States bear market of 2007–2009.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] It was also a contributor to the 2008–2011 Icelandic financial crisis and the euro area crisis.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] As the Federal Reserve ("Fed") lowered the federal funds rate from 2000 to 2003, institutions increasingly targeted low-income homebuyers, largely belonging to racial minorities, with high-risk loans; this development went unattended by regulators.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] As interest rates rose from 2004 to 2006, the cost of mortgages rose and the demand for housing fell; in early 2007, as more U.S. subprime mortgage holders began defaulting on their repayments, lenders went bankrupt, culminating in the bankruptcy of New Century Financial in April.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] As demand and prices continued to fall, the financial contagion spread to global credit markets by August 2007, and central banks began injecting liquidity.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In March 2008, Bear Stearns, the fifth-largest U.S. investment bank, was sold to JPMorgan Chase in a "fire sale" backed by Fed financing.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In response to the growing crisis, governments around the world deployed massive bailouts of financial institutions and used monetary policy and fiscal policies to prevent an economic collapse of the global financial system.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] By July 2008, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, companies which together owned or guaranteed half of the U.S. housing market, verged on collapse; the Housing and Economic Recovery Act of 2008 enabled the federal government to seize them on September 7.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] On October 3, Congress passed the Emergency Economic Stabilization Act, authorizing the Treasury Department to purchase toxic assets and bank stocks through the $700 billion Troubled Asset Relief Program (TARP).
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Fed began a program of quantitative easing by buying treasury bonds and other assets, such as MBS, and the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act, signed in February 2009 by newly elected president Barack Obama, included a range of measures intended to preserve existing jobs and create new ones.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] These initiatives combined, coupled with actions taken in other countries, ended the worst of the Great Recession by mid-2009.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Assessments of the crisis's impact in the U.S. vary, but suggest that some 8.7 million jobs were lost, causing unemployment to rise from 5% in 2007 to a high of 10% in October 2009.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The percentage of citizens living in poverty rose from 12.5% in 2007 to 15.1% in 2010.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell by 53% between October 2007 and March 2009, and some estimates suggest that one in four households lost 75% or more of their net worth.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In 2010, the Dodd–Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act was passed, overhauling financial regulations.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] It was opposed by many Republicans, and it was weakened by the Economic Growth, Regulatory Relief, and Consumer Protection Act in 2018.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Basel III capital and liquidity standards were also adopted by countries around the world.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The crisis exacerbated the Great Recession, a global recession that began in mid-2007.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] It was among the five worst financial crises the world had experienced and led to a loss of more than $2 trillion from the global economy.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] U.S. home mortgage debt relative to GDP increased from an average of 46% during the 1990s to 73% during 2008, reaching $10.5 (~$15 trillion in 2024) trillion.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The increase in cash out refinancings, as home values rose, fueled an increase in consumption that could no longer be sustained when home prices declined.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Many financial institutions owned investments whose value was based on home mortgages such as mortgage-backed securities, or credit derivatives used to insure them against failure, which declined in value significantly.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The International Monetary Fund estimated that large U.S. and European banks lost more than $1 trillion on toxic assets and from bad loans from January 2007 to September 2009.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Lack of investor confidence in bank solvency and declines in credit availability led to plummeting stock and commodity prices in late 2008 and early 2009.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The crisis rapidly spread into a global economic shock, resulting in several bank failures.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Economies worldwide slowed during this period since credit tightened and international trade declined.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Housing markets suffered and unemployment soared, resulting in evictions and foreclosures.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] From its peak in the second quarter of 2007 at $61.4 trillion, household wealth in the United States fell $11 trillion, to $50.4 trillion by the end of the first quarter of 2009, resulting in a decline in consumption, then a decline in business investment.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In the fourth quarter of 2008, the quarter-over-quarter decline in real GDP in the U.S. was 8.4%.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The U.S. unemployment rate peaked at 11.0% in October 2009, the highest rate since 1983 and roughly twice the pre-crisis rate.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The average hours per work week declined to 33, the lowest level since the government began collecting the data in 1964.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The economic crisis started in the U.S. but spread to the rest of the world.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] U.S. consumption accounted for more than a third of the growth in global consumption between 2000 and 2007 and the rest of the world depended on the U.S. consumer as a source of demand.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Toxic securities were owned by corporate and institutional investors globally.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Derivatives such as credit default swaps also increased the linkage between large financial institutions.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The de-leveraging of financial institutions, as assets were sold to pay back obligations that could not be refinanced in frozen credit markets, further accelerated the solvency crisis and caused a decrease in international trade.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Reductions in the growth rates of developing countries were due to falls in trade, commodity prices, investment and remittances sent from migrant workers (example: Armenia).
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] States with fragile political systems feared that investors from Western states would withdraw their money because of the crisis.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In effect, the central banks went from being the "lender of last resort" to the "lender of only resort" for a significant portion of the economy.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In some cases the Fed was considered the "buyer of last resort".
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] During the fourth quarter of 2008, these central banks purchased US$2.5 trillion (~$3.57 trillion in 2024) of government debt and troubled private assets from banks.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This was the largest liquidity injection into the credit market, and the largest monetary policy action in world history.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve created then-significant amounts of new currency as a method to combat the liquidity trap.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Bailouts came in the form of trillions of dollars of loans, asset purchases, guarantees, and direct spending.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Significant controversy accompanied the bailouts, such as in the case of the AIG bonus payments controversy, leading to the development of a variety of "decision making frameworks", to help balance competing policy interests during times of financial crisis.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Alistair Darling, the U.K.'s Chancellor of the Exchequer at the time of the crisis, stated in 2018 that Britain came within hours of "a breakdown of law and order" the day that Royal Bank of Scotland was bailed-out.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Instead of financing more domestic loans, some banks instead spent some of the stimulus money in more profitable areas such as investing in emerging markets and foreign currencies.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In July 2010, the Dodd–Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act was enacted in the United States to "promote the financial stability of the United States".
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Basel III capital and liquidity standards were adopted worldwide.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Since the 2008 financial crisis, consumer regulators in America have more closely supervised sellers of credit cards and home mortgages in order to deter anticompetitive practices that led to the crisis.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] At least two major reports on the causes of the crisis were produced by the U.S.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Congress: the Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission report, released January 2011, and a report by the United States Senate Homeland Security Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations entitled Wall Street and the Financial Crisis: Anatomy of a Financial Collapse, released April 2011.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In total, 47 bankers served jail time as a result of the crisis, over half of whom were from Iceland, where the crisis was the most severe and led to the collapse of all three major Icelandic banks.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In April 2012, Geir Haarde of Iceland became the only politician to be convicted as a result of the crisis.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In the aftermath of the crisis, U.S. authorities intensified enforcement actions against financial misconduct, including high-profile insider trading prosecutions such as that of Raj Rajaratnam, who was convicted in 2011.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Only one banker in the United States served jail time as a result of the crisis, Kareem Serageldin, a banker at Credit Suisse who was sentenced to 30 months in jail and returned $24.6 million in compensation for manipulating bond prices to hide $1 billion of losses.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] No individuals in the United Kingdom were convicted as a result of the crisis.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Goldman Sachs*, Goldman Sachs paid a $550 million civil penalty and acknowledged that its marketing materials for CDO contained incomplete information, settling securities fraud charges after allegedly anticipating the financial crisis and selling toxic investments to its clients.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] With fewer resources to risk in creative destruction, the number of patent applications was flat, compared to exponential increases in patent application in prior years.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Typical American families did not fare well, nor did the "wealthy-but-not-wealthiest" families just beneath the pyramid's top.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] However, half of the poorest families in the United States did not have wealth declines at all during the crisis because they generally did not own financial investments whose value could fluctuate.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve surveyed 4,000 households from 2007 to 2009, and found that the total wealth of 63% of all Americans declined in that period and 77% of the richest families had a decrease in total wealth, while only 50% of those on the bottom of the pyramid suffered a decrease.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The following is a timeline of the major events of the financial crisis, including government responses, and the subsequent economic recovery.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In the table, the names of emerging and developing economies are shown in boldface type, while the names of developed economies are in Roman (regular) type.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The expansion of central bank lending in response to the crisis was not confined to the Federal Reserve's provision of aid to individual financial institutions.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve has also conducted several innovative lending programs to improve liquidity and strengthen different financial institutions and markets, such as Freddie Mac and Fannie Mae.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In this case, the major problem in the market is the lack of free cash reserves and flows to secure the loans.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve took many steps to deal with financial market liquidity worries.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] One of these steps was a credit line for major traders, who act as the Fed's partners in open market activities.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Also, loan programs were set up to make the money market mutual funds and commercial paper market more flexible.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Also, the Term Asset-Backed Securities Loan Facility (TALF) was put in place thanks to a joint effort with the US Department of the Treasury.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This plan made it easier for consumers and businesses to get credit by giving Americans who owned high-quality asset-backed securities more credit.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Before the crisis, the Federal Reserve's stocks of Treasury securities were sold to pay for the increase in credit.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This method was meant to keep banks from trying to give out their extra savings, which could cause the federal funds rate to drop below where it was supposed to be.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] However, in October 2008, the Federal Reserve was granted the power to provide banks with interest payments on their surplus reserves.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This created a motivation for banks to retain their reserves instead of disbursing them, thus reducing the need for the Federal Reserve to hedge its increased lending by decreases in alternative assets.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Money market funds also went through runs when people lost faith in the market.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] To keep it from getting worse, the Fed said it would give money to mutual fund companies.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Also, the Department of Treasury said that it would briefly cover the assets of the fund.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Both of these things helped get the fund market back to normal, which helped the commercial paper market, which most businesses use to run.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The FDIC also did several things, such as raising the insurance cap from $100,000 to $250,000, to boost customer trust.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] They engaged in quantitative easing, which added more than $4 trillion to the financial system and got banks to start lending again, both to each other and to people.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Many homeowners who were trying to keep their homes from going into default got housing credits.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p01] A package of policies was passed that let borrowers refinance their loans even though the value of their homes was less than what they still owed on their mortgages.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The relaxing of credit lending standards by investment banks and commercial banks allowed for a significant increase in subprime lending.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Subprime had not become less risky; Wall Street just accepted this higher risk.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Due to competition between mortgage lenders for revenue and market share, and when the supply of creditworthy borrowers was limited, mortgage lenders relaxed underwriting standards and originated riskier mortgages to less creditworthy borrowers.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In the view of some analysts, the relatively conservative government-sponsored enterprises (GSEs) policed mortgage originators and maintained relatively high underwriting standards prior to 2003.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] However, as market power shifted from securitizers to originators, and as intense competition from private securitizers undermined GSE power, mortgage standards declined and risky loans proliferated.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The riskiest loans were originated in 2004–2007, the years of the most intense competition between securitizers and the lowest market share for the GSEs.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The GSEs eventually relaxed their standards to try to catch up with the private banks.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Depending on how "subprime" mortgages are defined, they remained below 10% of all mortgage originations until 2004, when they rose to nearly 20% and remained there through the 2005–2006 peak of the United States housing bubble.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Although they concede that governmental policies had some role in causing the crisis, they contend that GSE loans performed better than loans securitized by private investment banks, and performed better than some loans originated by institutions that held loans in their own portfolios.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In his dissent to the majority report of the Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission, conservative American Enterprise Institute fellow Peter J.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Based upon information in the SEC's December 2011 securities fraud case against six former executives of Fannie and Freddie, Peter Wallison and Edward Pinto estimated that, in 2008, Fannie and Freddie held 13 million substandard loans totaling over $2 trillion.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In the early and mid-2000s, the Bush administration called numerous times for investigations into the safety and soundness of the GSEs and their swelling portfolio of subprime mortgages.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The hearings never resulted in new legislation or formal investigation of Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, as many of the committee members refused to accept the report and instead rebuked OFHEO for their attempt at regulation.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Some, such as Wallison, believe this was an early warning to the systemic risk that the growing market in subprime mortgages posed to the U.S. financial system that went unheeded.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Sub-prime loans made by CRA-covered institutions constituted a 3% market share of LMI loans in 1998, but in the run-up to the crisis, fully 25% of all subprime lending occurred at CRA-covered institutions and another 25% of subprime loans had some connection with CRA.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] To other analysts the delay between CRA rule changes in 1995 and the explosion of subprime lending is not surprising, and does not exonerate the CRA.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] They contend that there were two, connected causes to the crisis: the relaxation of underwriting standards in 1995 and the ultra-low interest rates initiated by the Federal Reserve after the terrorist attack on September 11, 2001.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Both causes had to be in place before the crisis could take place.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Critics also point out that publicly announced CRA loan commitments were massive, totaling $4.5 trillion in the years between 1994 and 2007.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] They also argue that the Federal Reserve's classification of CRA loans as "prime" is based on the faulty and self-serving assumption that high-interest-rate loans (3 percentage points over average) equal "subprime" loans.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Others have pointed out that there were not enough of these loans made to cause a crisis of this magnitude.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By March 2011, the FDIC had paid out $9 billion (c. $12.3 billion in 2024) to cover losses on bad loans at 165 failed financial institutions.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The Congressional Budget Office estimated, in June 2011, that the bailout to Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac exceeds $300 billion (c. $411 billion in 2024) (calculated by adding the fair value deficits of the entities to the direct bailout funds at the time).
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In other words, bubbles in both markets developed even though only the residential market was affected by these potential causes.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] *residential housing* bubble (as opposed to other types of bubbles) led to financial crisis was that it was supported by a huge number of substandard loans—generally with low or no downpayments.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Krugman's contention (that the growth of a commercial real estate bubble indicates that U.S. housing policy was not the cause of the crisis) is challenged by additional analysis.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] After researching the default of commercial loans during the financial crisis, Xudong An and Anthony B.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Business journalist Kimberly Amadeo reported: "The first signs of decline in residential real estate occurred in 2006.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Three years later, commercial real estate started feeling the effects." Denice A.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Between 1998 and 2006, the price of the typical American house increased by 124%.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] During the 1980s and 1990s, the national median home price ranged from 2.9 to 3.1 times median household income.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By contrast, this ratio increased to 4.0 in 2004, and 4.6 in 2006.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This housing bubble resulted in many homeowners refinancing their homes at lower interest rates, or financing consumer spending by taking out second mortgages secured by the price appreciation.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In a Peabody Award-winning program, NPR correspondents argued that a "Giant Pool of Money" (represented by $70 trillion in worldwide fixed income investments) sought higher yields than those offered by U.S.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This pool of money had roughly doubled in size from 2000 to 2007, yet the supply of relatively safe, income generating investments had not grown as fast.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Investment banks on Wall Street answered this demand with products such as the mortgage-backed security and the collateralized debt obligation that were assigned safe ratings by the credit rating agencies.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In effect, Wall Street connected this pool of money to the mortgage market in the US, with enormous fees accruing to those throughout the mortgage supply chain, from the mortgage broker selling the loans to small banks that funded the brokers and the large investment banks behind them.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By approximately 2003, the supply of mortgages originated at traditional lending standards had been exhausted, and continued strong demand began to drive down lending standards.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The collateralized debt obligation in particular enabled financial institutions to obtain investor funds to finance subprime and other lending, extending or increasing the housing bubble and generating large fees.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This essentially places cash payments from multiple mortgages or other debt obligations into a single pool from which specific securities draw in a specific sequence of priority.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Those securities first in line received investment-grade ratings from rating agencies.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Securities with lower priority had lower credit ratings but theoretically a higher rate of return on the amount invested.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By September 2008, average U.S. housing prices had declined by over 20% from their mid-2006 peak.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] As prices declined, borrowers with adjustable-rate mortgages could not refinance to avoid the higher payments associated with rising interest rates and began to default.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] During 2007, lenders began foreclosure proceedings on nearly 1.3 million properties, a 79% increase over 2006.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This increased to 2.3 million in 2008, an 81% increase vs.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By August 2008, approximately 9% of all U.S. mortgages outstanding were either delinquent or in foreclosure.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By September 2009, this had risen to 14.4%.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] After the bubble burst, Australian economist John Quiggin wrote: "And, unlike the Great Depression, this crisis was entirely the product of financial markets.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Lower interest rates encouraged borrowing.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] From 2000 to 2003, the Federal Reserve lowered the federal funds rate target from 6.5% to 1.0%.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This was done to soften the effects of the collapse of the dot-com bubble and the September 11 attacks, as well as to combat a perceived risk of deflation.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] As early as 2002, it was apparent that credit was fueling housing instead of business investment as some economists went so far as to advocate that the Fed "needs to create a housing bubble to replace the Nasdaq bubble".
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Moreover, empirical studies using data from advanced countries show that excessive credit growth contributed greatly to the severity of the crisis.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Additional downward pressure on interest rates was created by a growing U.S. current account deficit, which peaked along with the housing bubble in 2006.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Federal Reserve chairman Ben Bernanke explained how trade deficits required the U.S. to borrow money from abroad, in the process bidding up bond prices and lowering interest rates.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Bernanke explained that between 1996 and 2004, the U.S. current account deficit increased by $650 billion, from 1.5% to 5.8% of GDP.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Financing these deficits required the country to borrow large sums from abroad, much of it from countries running trade surpluses.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] These were mainly the emerging economies in Asia and oil-exporting nations.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The balance of payments identity requires that a country (such as the US) running a current account deficit also have a capital account (investment) surplus of the same amount.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Hence large and growing amounts of foreign funds (capital) flowed into the U.S. to finance its imports.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] All of this created demand for various types of financial assets, raising the prices of those assets while lowering interest rates.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Foreign investors had these funds to lend either because they had very high personal savings rates (as high as 40% in China) or because of high oil prices.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Ben Bernanke referred to this as a "saving glut".
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] A flood of funds (capital or liquidity) reached the U.S. financial markets.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Foreign governments supplied funds by purchasing Treasury bonds and thus avoided much of the direct effect of the crisis.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] U.S. households used funds borrowed from foreigners to finance consumption or to bid up the prices of housing and financial assets.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Financial institutions invested foreign funds in mortgage-backed securities.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The Fed then raised the Fed funds rate significantly between July 2004 and July 2006.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This contributed to an increase in one-year and five-year adjustable-rate mortgage (ARM) rates, making ARM interest rate resets more expensive for homeowners.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This may have also contributed to the deflation of the housing bubble, as asset prices generally move inversely to interest rates.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] It became riskier to speculate in housing.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] U.S. housing and financial assets dramatically declined in value after the housing bubble burst.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Subprime lending standards declined in the U.S.: in early 2000, a subprime borrower had a FICO score of 660 or less.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By 2005, many lenders dropped the required FICO score to 620, making it much easier to qualify for prime loans and making subprime lending a riskier business.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Proof of income and assets were de-emphasized.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Loans at first required full documentation, then low documentation, then no documentation.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] One subprime mortgage product that gained wide acceptance was the no income, no job, no asset verification required (NINJA) mortgage.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Informally, these loans were aptly referred to as "liar loans" because they encouraged borrowers to be less than honest in the loan application process.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Testimony given to the Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission by whistleblower Richard M.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Bowen III on events during his tenure as the Business Chief Underwriter for Correspondent Lending in the Consumer Lending Group for Citigroup, where he was responsible for over 220 professional underwriters, suggests that by 2006 and 2007, the collapse of mortgage underwriting standards was endemic.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] His testimony stated that by 2006, 60% of mortgages purchased by Citigroup from some 1,600 mortgage companies were "defective" (were not underwritten to policy, or did not contain all policy-required documents).
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This, despite the fact that each of these 1,600 originators was contractually responsible (certified via representations and warrantees) that its mortgage originations met Citigroup standards.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Moreover, during 2007, "defective mortgages (from mortgage originators contractually bound to perform underwriting to Citi's standards) increased to over 80% of production".
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The analysis, conducted on behalf of 23 investment and commercial banks, including 7 "too big to fail" banks, additionally showed that 28% of the sampled loans did not meet the minimal standards of any issuer.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Clayton's analysis further showed that 39% of these loans (i.e. those not meeting *any* issuer's minimal underwriting standards) were subsequently securitized and sold to investors.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Predatory lending refers to the practice of unscrupulous lenders enticing borrowers to enter into unfair or abusive secured loans for inappropriate purposes.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In May 2009, Bank of America modified 64,000 Countrywide loans as a result.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] When housing prices decreased, homeowners in ARMs then had little incentive to pay their monthly payments, since their home equity had disappeared.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This caused Countrywide's financial condition to deteriorate, ultimately resulting in a decision by the Office of Thrift Supervision to seize the lender.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Former employees from Ameriquest, which was the United States' leading wholesale lender, described a system in which they were pushed to falsify mortgage documents and then sell the mortgages to Wall Street banks eager to make fast profits.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] There is growing evidence that such mortgage frauds may be a cause of the crisis.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] According to Barry Eichengreen, the roots of the financial crisis lay in the deregulation of financial markets.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] A 2012 OECD study suggested that bank regulation based on the Basel accords encouraged unconventional business practices and contributed to or reinforced the financial crisis.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In other cases, laws were changed or enforcement weakened in parts of the financial system.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Prior to the crisis, financial institutions became highly leveraged, increasing their appetite for risky investments and reducing their resilience in case of losses.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Much of this leverage was achieved using complex financial instruments such as off-balance sheet securitization and derivatives, which made it difficult for creditors and regulators to monitor and try to reduce financial institution risk levels.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] U.S. households and financial institutions became increasingly indebted or overleveraged during the years preceding the crisis.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This increased their vulnerability to the collapse of the housing bubble and worsened the ensuing economic downturn.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Free cash used by consumers from home equity extraction doubled from $627 billion in 2001 to $1,428 billion in 2005 as the housing bubble built, a total of nearly $5 trillion over the period, contributing to economic growth worldwide.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p02] U.S. home mortgage debt relative to GDP increased from an average of 46% during the 1990s to 73% during 2008, reaching $10.5 trillion (c. $15 trillion in 2024).
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] U.S. household debt as a percentage of annual disposable personal income was 127% at the end of 2007, versus 77% in 1990.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 1981, U.S. private debt was 123% of GDP; by the third quarter of 2008, it was 290%.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] From 2004 to 2007, the top five U.S. investment banks each significantly increased their financial leverage, which increased their vulnerability to a financial shock.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Changes in capital requirements, intended to keep U.S. banks competitive with their European counterparts, allowed lower *risk weightings* for AAA-rated securities.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The shift from first-loss tranches to AAA-rated tranches was seen by regulators as a risk reduction that compensated the higher leverage.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These five institutions reported over $4.1 trillion in debt for fiscal year 2007, about 30% of U.S. nominal GDP for 2007.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Lehman Brothers went bankrupt and was liquidated, Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch were sold at fire-sale prices, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley became commercial banks, subjecting themselves to more stringent regulation.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] With the exception of Lehman, these companies required or received government support.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, two U.S. government-sponsored enterprises, owned or guaranteed nearly $5 trillion (c. $7.13 trillion in 2024) trillion in mortgage obligations at the time they were placed into conservatorship by the U.S. government in September 2008.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These seven entities were highly leveraged and had $9 trillion in debt or guarantee obligations; yet they were not subject to the same regulation as depository banks.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Behavior that may be optimal for an individual, such as saving more during adverse economic conditions, can be detrimental if too many individuals pursue the same behavior, as ultimately one person's consumption is another person's income.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Too many consumers attempting to save or pay down debt simultaneously is called the paradox of thrift and can cause or deepen a recession.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economist Hyman Minsky also described a "paradox of deleveraging" as financial institutions that have too much leverage (debt relative to equity) cannot all de-leverage simultaneously without significant declines in the value of their assets.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The term financial innovation refers to the ongoing development of financial products designed to achieve particular client objectives, such as offsetting a particular risk exposure (such as the default of a borrower) or to assist with obtaining financing.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The usage of these products expanded dramatically in the years leading up to the crisis.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These products vary in complexity and the ease with which they can be valued on the books of financial institutions.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] CDO issuance grew from an estimated $20 billion in Q1 2004 to its peak of over $180 billion by Q1 2007, then declined back under $20 billion by Q1 2008.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Further, the credit quality of CDO's declined from 2000 to 2007, as the level of subprime and other non-prime mortgage debt increased from 5% to 36% of CDO assets.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As described in the section on subprime lending, the CDS and portfolio of CDS called synthetic CDO enabled a theoretically infinite amount to be wagered on the finite value of housing loans outstanding, provided that buyers and sellers of the derivatives could be found.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] For example, buying a CDS to insure a CDO ended up giving the seller the same risk as if they owned the CDO, when those CDO's became worthless.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This boom in innovative financial products went hand in hand with more complexity.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] It multiplied the number of actors connected to a single mortgage (including mortgage brokers, specialized originators, the securitizers and their due diligence firms, managing agents and trading desks, and finally investors, insurances and providers of repo funding).
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Instead of spreading risk this provided the ground for fraudulent acts, misjudgments and finally market collapse.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economists have studied the crisis as an instance of cascades in financial networks, where institutions' instability destabilized other institutions and led to knock-on effects.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Mortgage risks were underestimated by almost all institutions in the chain from originator to investor by underweighting the possibility of falling housing prices based on historical trends of the past 50 years.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] While financial derivatives and structured products helped partition and shift risk between financial participants, it was the underestimation of falling housing prices and the resultant losses that led to aggregate risk.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] For a variety of reasons, market participants did not accurately measure the risk inherent with financial innovation such as MBS and CDOs or understand its effect on the overall stability of the financial system.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The pricing model for CDOs clearly did not reflect the level of risk they introduced into the system.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] AIG insured obligations of various financial institutions through the usage of credit default swaps.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The basic CDS transaction involved AIG receiving a premium in exchange for a promise to pay money to party A in the event party B defaulted.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] However, AIG did not have the financial strength to support its many CDS commitments as the crisis progressed and was taken over by the government in September 2008.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] U.S. taxpayers provided over $180 billion in government loans and investments in AIG during 2008 and early 2009, through which the money flowed to various counterparties to CDS transactions, including many large global financial institutions.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission (FCIC) made the major government study of the crisis.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The limitations of a widely used financial model also were not properly understood.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This formula assumed that the price of CDS was correlated with and could predict the correct price of mortgage-backed securities.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Because it was highly tractable, it rapidly came to be used by a huge percentage of CDO and CDS investors, issuers, and rating agencies.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As financial assets became more complex and harder to value, investors were reassured by the fact that the international bond rating agencies and bank regulators accepted as valid some complex mathematical models that showed the risks were much smaller than they actually were.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] George Soros commented that "The super-boom got out of hand when the new products became so complicated that the authorities could no longer calculate the risks and started relying on the risk management methods of the banks themselves.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Similarly, the rating agencies relied on the information provided by the originators of synthetic products.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] A conflict of interest between investment management professional and institutional investors, combined with a global glut in investment capital, led to bad investments by asset managers in over-priced credit assets.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Professional investment managers generally are compensated based on the volume of client assets under management.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] There is, therefore, an incentive for asset managers to expand their assets under management in order to maximize their compensation.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As the glut in global investment capital caused the yields on credit assets to decline, asset managers were faced with the choice of either investing in assets where returns did not reflect true credit risk or returning funds to clients.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Many asset managers continued to invest client funds in over-priced (under-yielding) investments, to the detriment of their clients, so they could maintain their assets under management.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] They supported this choice with a "plausible deniability" of the risks associated with subprime-based credit assets because the loss experience with early "vintages" of subprime loans was so low.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Despite the dominance of the above formula, there are documented attempts of the financial industry, occurring before the crisis, to address the formula limitations, specifically the lack of dependence dynamics and the poor representation of extreme events.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The volume *Credit Correlation: Life After Copulas*, published in 2007 by World Scientific, summarizes a 2006 conference held by Merrill Lynch in London where several practitioners attempted to propose models rectifying some of the copula limitations.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] See also the article by Donnelly and Embrechts and the book by Brigo, Pallavicini and Torresetti, that reports relevant warnings and research on CDOs appeared in 2006.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] There is strong evidence that the riskiest, worst performing mortgages were funded through the "shadow banking system" and that competition from the shadow banking system may have pressured more traditional institutions to lower their underwriting standards and originate riskier loans.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These entities became critical to the credit markets underpinning the financial system, but were not subject to the same regulatory controls.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Further, these entities were vulnerable because of asset–liability mismatch, meaning that they borrowed short-term in liquid markets to purchase long-term, illiquid and risky assets.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This meant that disruptions in credit markets would force them to engage in rapid deleveraging, selling their long-term assets at depressed prices.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economist Paul Krugman, laureate of the Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences, described the run on the shadow banking system as the "core of what happened" to cause the crisis.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] He referred to this lack of controls as "malign neglect" and argued that regulation should have been imposed on all banking-like activity.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Without the ability to obtain investor funds in exchange for most types of mortgage-backed securities or asset-backed commercial paper, investment banks and other entities in the shadow banking system could not provide funds to mortgage firms and other corporations.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This meant that nearly one-third of the U.S. lending mechanism was frozen and continued to be frozen into June 2009.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] While traditional banks raised their lending standards, it was the collapse of the shadow banking system that was the primary cause of the reduction in funds available for borrowing.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Caballero, Emmanuel Farhi, and Pierre-Olivier Gourinchas argued that the financial crisis was attributable to "global asset scarcity, which led to large capital flows toward the United States and to the creation of asset bubbles that eventually burst".
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Long-only commodity index funds became popular – by one estimate investment increased from $90 billion in 2006 to $200 billion at the end of 2007, while commodity prices increased 71% – which raised concern as to whether these index funds caused the commodity bubble.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The cause of the global asset bubble can be partially attributable to the global savings glut.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As theorized by Andrew Metrick, the demand for safe assets following the Asian Financial Crisis coupled with the lack of circulating treasuries created an unmet demand for "risk free" assets.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Thus, institutional investors like sovereign wealth funds and pension funds began purchasing synthetic safe assets like Triple-A Mortgage Backed Securities.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As a consequence, the demand for so-called safe assets fueled the free flow of capital into housing in the United States.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This greatly worsened the crisis as banks and other financial institutions were incentivized to issue more mortgages than before.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Some commentators and economists associated with the Austrian School of economics, including former U.S.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Congressman Ron Paul and historian Tom Woods, have offered a libertarian interpretation of the crisis which differs from the explanations centered on deregulation and government oversight.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In Ron Paul's book, *End the Fed,* Paul argues that the Federal Reserve's prolonged policy of artificially low interest rates in the early 2000s created a credit bubble that allowed for speculative investments and unsustainable levels of debt, particularly in housing.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In Tom Woods' book *Meltdown*, he also contends that Federal Reserve manipulation of the money supply and credit markets distorted normal price signals, leading to widespread malinvestment, resulting in an inevitable correction.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Paul and Woods also criticized Fannie Mae's and Freddie Mac's role in the crisis, asserting that the entities engaged in excessive risk-taking by expanding homeownership beyond sustainable levels.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In doing this, the government intervention created moral hazard by assuring large financial institutions that they would receive government support in times of crisis, which Paul and Woods believe encouraged riskier behavior.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In a 1998 book, John McMurtry suggested that a financial crisis is a systemic crisis of capitalism itself.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In his 1978 book, *The Downfall of Capitalism and Communism*, Ravi Batra suggests that growing inequality of financial capitalism produces speculative bubbles that burst and result in depression and major political changes.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] He also suggested that a "demand gap" related to differing wage and productivity growth explains deficit and debt dynamics important to stock market developments.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] John Bellamy Foster, a political economy analyst and editor of the *Monthly Review*, believed that the decrease in GDP growth rates since the early 1970s is due to increasing market saturation.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Marxian economics followers Andrew Kliman, Michael Roberts, and Guglielmo Carchedi, in contradistinction to the *Monthly Review* school represented by Foster, pointed to capitalism's long-term tendency of the rate of profit to fall as the underlying cause of crises generally.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] From this point of view, the problem was the inability of capital to grow or accumulate at sufficient rates through productive investment alone.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Low rates of profit in productive sectors led to speculative investment in riskier assets, where there was potential for greater return on investment.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The speculative frenzy of the late 1990s and 2000s was, in this view, a consequence of a rising organic composition of capital, expressed through the fall in the rate of profit.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] According to Michael Roberts, the fall in the rate of profit "eventually triggered the credit crunch of 2007 when credit could no longer support profits".
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 2005 book, *The Battle for the Soul of Capitalism*, John C.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Bogle wrote that "Corporate America went astray largely because the power of managers went virtually unchecked by our gatekeepers for far too long".
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In his book *The Big Mo*, Mark Roeder, a former executive at the Swiss-based UBS Bank, suggested that large-scale momentum, or The Big Mo, "played a pivotal role" in the financial crisis.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Roeder suggested that "recent technological advances, such as computer-driven trading programs, together with the increasingly interconnected nature of markets, has magnified the momentum effect.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Robert Reich attributed the economic downturn to the stagnation of wages in the United States, particularly those of the hourly workers who comprise 80% of the workforce.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This stagnation forced the population to borrow to meet the cost of living.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economists Ailsa McKay and Margunn Bjørnholt argued that the financial crisis and the response to it revealed a crisis of ideas in mainstream economics and within the economics profession, and call for a reshaping of both the economy, economic theory and the economics profession.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] A report by the International Labour Organization concluded that cooperative banking institutions were less likely to fail than their competitors during the crisis.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The cooperative banking sector had 20% market share of the European banking sector, but accounted for only 7% of all the write-downs and losses between the third quarter of 2007 and first quarter of 2011.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 2008, in the U.S., the rate of commercial bank failures was almost triple that of credit unions, and almost five times the credit union rate in 2010.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Credit unions increased their lending to small- and medium-sized businesses while overall lending to those businesses decreased.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economists, particularly followers of mainstream economics, mostly failed to predict the crisis.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Several followers of heterodox economics predicted the crisis, with varying arguments.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Dirk Bezemer credits 12 economists with predicting the crisis: Dean Baker, Wynne Godley, Fred Harrison, Michael Hudson, Eric Janszen, Med Jones, Steve Keen, Jakob Broechner Madsen & Jens Kjaer Sørensen, Kurt Richebächer, Nouriel Roubini, Peter Schiff, and Robert Shiller.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Shiller, a founder of the Case–Shiller index that measures home prices, wrote an article a year before the collapse of Lehman Brothers in which he predicted that a slowing U.S. housing market would cause the housing bubble to burst, leading to financial collapse.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Peter Schiff regularly appeared on television in the years before the crisis and warned of the impending real estate collapse.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The Austrian School regarded the crisis as a vindication and classic example of a predictable credit-fueled bubble caused by laxity in monetary supply.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] There were other economists that did warn of a pending crisis.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The former Governor of the Reserve Bank of India, Raghuram Rajan, had predicted the crisis in 2005 when he became chief economist at the International Monetary Fund.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 2005, at a celebration honoring Alan Greenspan, who was about to retire as chairman of the US Federal Reserve, Rajan delivered a controversial paper that was critical of the financial sector.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In that paper, Rajan "argued that disaster might loom".
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Rajan argued that financial sector managers were encouraged to "take risks that generate severe adverse consequences with small probability but, in return, offer generous compensation the rest of the time.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] He also took action against the establishment view by making a big financial bet on banking stocks and making a fortune from the crisis ("They didn't listen, so I took their money").
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Popular articles published in the mass media have led the general public to believe that the majority of economists have failed in their obligation to predict the financial crisis.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] For example, an article in *The New York Times* noted that economist Nouriel Roubini warned of such crisis as early as September 2006, and stated that the profession of economics is bad at predicting recessions.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] According to *The Guardian*, Roubini was ridiculed for predicting a collapse of the housing market and worldwide recession, while *The New York Times* labelled him "Dr.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In a 2012 article in the journal *Japan and the World Economy*, Andrew K.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Spiegel used a Multiple Indicator Multiple Cause (MIMIC) model on a cross-section of 107 countries to evaluate potential causes of the 2008 crisis.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The authors examined various economic indicators, ignoring contagion effects across countries.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Despite the fact that we use a wide number of possible causes in a flexible statistical framework, we are unable to link most of the commonly cited causes of the crisis to its incidence across countries.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The first visible institution to run into trouble in the United States was the Southern California–based IndyMac, a spin-off of Countrywide Financial.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Before its failure, IndyMac Bank was the largest savings and loan association in the Los Angeles market and the seventh-largest mortgage loan originator in the United States.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The failure of IndyMac Bank on July 11, 2008, was (until the crisis precipitated even larger failures) the fourth-largest bank failure in United States history, and the second-largest failure of a regulated thrift.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac Bank's parent corporation was IndyMac Bancorp until the FDIC seized IndyMac Bank.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac Bancorp filed for Chapter 7 bankruptcy in July 2008.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac Bank was founded as Countrywide Mortgage Investment in 1985 by David S.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Loeb and Angelo Mozilo as a means of collateralizing Countrywide Financial loans too big to be sold to Freddie Mac and Fannie Mae.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 1997, Countrywide spun off IndyMac as an independent company run by Mike Perry, who remained its CEO until the downfall of the bank in July 2008.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The primary causes of its failure were largely associated with its business strategy of originating and securitizing Alt-A loans on a large scale.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This strategy resulted in rapid growth and a high concentration of risky assets.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] From its inception as a savings association in 2000, IndyMac grew to the seventh largest savings and loan and ninth largest originator of mortgage loans in the United States.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] During 2006, IndyMac originated over $90 billion (~$134 billion in 2024) of mortgages.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac often made loans without verification of the borrower's income or assets, and to borrowers with poor credit histories.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Appraisals obtained by IndyMac on underlying collateral were often questionable as well.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As an Alt-A lender, IndyMac's business model was to offer loan products to fit the borrower's needs, using an extensive array of risky option-adjustable-rate mortgages (option ARMs), subprime loans, 80/20 loans, and other nontraditional products.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Ultimately, loans were made to many borrowers who simply could not afford to make their payments.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The thrift remained profitable only as long as it was able to sell those loans in the secondary mortgage market.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac resisted efforts to regulate its involvement in those loans or tighten their issuing criteria: see the comment by Ruthann Melbourne, Chief Risk Officer, to the regulating agencies.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] On May 12, 2008, in the "Capital" section of its last 10-Q, IndyMac revealed that it may not be well capitalized in the future.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac reported that during April 2008, Moody's and Standard & Poor's downgraded the ratings on a significant number of Mortgage-backed security (MBS) bonds—including $160 million (~$228 million in 2024) issued by IndyMac that the bank retained in its MBS portfolio.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac concluded that these downgrades would have harmed its risk-based capital ratio as of June 30, 2008.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Had these lowered ratings been in effect on March 31, 2008, IndyMac concluded that the bank's capital ratio would have been 9.27% total risk-based.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac warned that if its regulators found its capital position to have fallen below "well capitalized" (minimum 10% risk-based capital ratio) to "adequately capitalized" (8–10% risk-based capital ratio) the bank might no longer be able to use brokered deposits as a source of funds.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Senator Charles Schumer (D-NY) later pointed out that brokered deposits made up more than 37% of IndyMac's total deposits, and asked the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation (FDIC) whether it had considered ordering IndyMac to reduce its reliance on these deposits.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] With $18.9 billion in total deposits reported on March 31, Senator Schumer would have been referring to a little over $7 billion in brokered deposits.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] While the breakout of maturities of these deposits is not known exactly, a simple averaging would have put the threat of brokered deposits loss to IndyMac at $500 million a month, had the regulator disallowed IndyMac from acquiring new brokered deposits on June 30.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac was taking new measures to preserve capital, such as deferring interest payments on some preferred securities.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Dividends on common shares had already been suspended for the first quarter of 2008, after being cut in half the previous quarter.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The company still had not secured a significant capital infusion nor found a ready buyer.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac reported that the bank's risk-based capital was only $47 million above the minimum required for this 10% mark.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] But it did not reveal some of that $47 million (~$67 million in 2024) capital it claimed it had, as of March 31, 2008, was fabricated.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] When home prices declined in the latter half of 2007 and the secondary mortgage market collapsed, IndyMac was forced to hold $10.7 billion (~$15.5 billion in 2024) of loans it could not sell in the secondary market.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Its reduced liquidity was further exacerbated in late June 2008 when account holders withdrew $1.55 billion (~$2.21 billion in 2024) or about 7.5% of IndyMac's deposits.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This bank run on the thrift followed the public release of a letter from Senator Charles Schumer to the FDIC and OTS.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The letter outlined the Senator's concerns with IndyMac.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] While the run was a contributing factor in the timing of IndyMac's demise, the underlying cause of the failure was the unsafe and unsound way it was operated.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac announced the closure of both its retail lending and wholesale divisions, halted new loan submissions, and cut 3,800 jobs.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] On July 11, 2008, citing liquidity concerns, the FDIC put IndyMac Bank into conservatorship.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] A bridge bank, IndyMac Federal Bank, FSB, was established to assume control of IndyMac Bank's assets, its secured liabilities, and its insured deposit accounts.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The FDIC announced plans to open IndyMac Federal Bank, FSB on July 14, 2008.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Until then, depositors would have access to their insured deposits through ATMs, their existing checks, and their existing debit cards.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Telephone and Internet account access was restored when the bank reopened.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The FDIC guarantees the funds of all insured accounts up to US$100,000, and declared a special advance dividend to the roughly 10,000 depositors with funds in excess of the insured amount, guaranteeing 50% of any amounts in excess of $100,000.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Yet, even with the pending sale of Indymac to IMB Management Holdings, an estimated 10,000 uninsured depositors of Indymac are still at a loss of over $270 million.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] With $32 billion in assets, IndyMac Bank was one of the largest bank failures in American history.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac Bancorp filed for Chapter 7 bankruptcy on July 31, 2008.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Initially the companies affected were those directly involved in home construction and mortgage lending such as Northern Rock and Countrywide Financial, as they could no longer obtain financing through the credit markets.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Over 100 mortgage lenders went bankrupt during 2007 and 2008.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Concerns that investment bank Bear Stearns would collapse in March 2008 resulted in its fire-sale to JP Morgan Chase.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The financial institution crisis hit its peak in September and October 2008.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Several major institutions either failed, were acquired under duress, or were subject to government takeover.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These included Lehman Brothers, Merrill Lynch, Fannie Mae, Freddie Mac, Washington Mutual, Wachovia, Citigroup, and AIG.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] On October 6, 2008, three weeks after Lehman Brothers filed the largest bankruptcy in U.S. history, Lehman's former CEO Richard S.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Fuld Jr. found himself before Representative Henry A.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Waxman, the California Democrat who chaired the House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform.
[src:austerity/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Fuld said he was a victim of the collapse, blaming a "crisis of confidence" in the markets for dooming his firm.
[src:austerity/2008-latvian-financial-crisis] The **2008 Latvian financial crisis**, which stemmed from the 2008 global financial crisis, was a major economic and political crisis in Latvia.
[src:austerity/2008-latvian-financial-crisis] The crisis was generated when an easy credit market burst, resulting in an unemployment crisis, along with the bankruptcy of many companies.
[src:austerity/2008-latvian-financial-crisis] Since 2010, economic activity has recovered and Latvia's economic growth rate was the fastest among the EU member states in the first three quarters of 2012.
[src:austerity/2008-latvian-financial-crisis] In 2008, following years of booming economic success, the Latvian economy took one of the sharpest downturns in the world, picking up pace in the last quarter in which GDP contracted by 10.5%.
[src:austerity/2008-latvian-financial-crisis] In February 2009 the Latvian government asked the International Monetary Fund and the European Union for an emergency bailout loan of 7.5 billion Euros, while at the same time the government nationalized Parex Bank, the country's second largest bank.
[src:austerity/2008-latvian-financial-crisis] On concerns of bankruptcy, Standard & Poors subsequently downgraded Latvia's credit rating to non-investment grade BB+, or "junk", its worst ever rating.
[src:austerity/2008-latvian-financial-crisis] Its rating was put on negative outlook, which indicates a possible further cut.
[src:austerity/2008-latvian-financial-crisis] On February 20 the Latvian coalition government headed by Prime Minister of Latvia Ivars Godmanis collapsed.
[src:austerity/2008-latvian-financial-crisis] The Baltic states were amongst the worst hit by the Great Recession.
[src:austerity/2008-latvian-financial-crisis] In December 2008, the Latvian unemployment rate stood at 7%.
[src:austerity/2008-latvian-financial-crisis] By December 2009, the figure had risen to 22.8%.
[src:austerity/2008-latvian-financial-crisis] The number of unemployed has more than tripled since the onset of the crisis, giving Latvia the highest rate of unemployment growth in the EU.
[src:austerity/2008-latvian-financial-crisis] Early 2009 estimates predicted that the economy would contract by around 12% in 2009, but even those gloomy forecasts turned out to be too optimistic as the economy contracted by nearly 18% in the fourth quarter of 2009, showing little signs of recovery.
[src:austerity/2008-latvian-financial-crisis] However, by 2010 commentators noted signs of stabilisation in the Latvian economy.
[src:austerity/2008-latvian-financial-crisis] Rating agency Standard & Poor's raised its outlook on Latvia's debt from negative to stable.
[src:austerity/2008-latvian-financial-crisis] Latvia's current account, which had been in deficit by 27% in late 2006 was in surplus in February 2010.
[src:austerity/2008-latvian-financial-crisis] In June 2012 International Monetary Fund Managing Director Christine Lagarde lauded Latvia's accomplishments in bringing order to the country's economy, and emphasized Latvia must complete three more tasks - strive to join the eurozone, promote economic competitiveness, reduce social inequality.
[src:austerity/2008-latvian-financial-crisis] She concluded that by implementing its international loan program, Latvia has proven that it can be powerful and disciplined.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] The **2010–2014 Portuguese financial crisis** was part of the wider downturn of the Portuguese economy that started in 2001 and possibly ended between 2016 and 2017.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] The period from 2010 to 2014 was probably the hardest and more challenging part of the entire economic crisis; this period includes the 2011–14 international bailout to Portugal and was marked by intense austerity policies, more intense than the wider 2001-2017 crisis.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Economic growth stalled in Portugal between 2001 and 2002, and following years of internal economic crisis, the worldwide Great Recession started to hit Portugal in 2008 and eventually led to the country being unable to repay or refinance its government debt without the assistance of third parties.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] To prevent an insolvency situation in the debt crisis, Portugal applied in April 2011 for bail-out programs and drew a cumulated €78 billion from the IMF, the EFSM, and the EFSF.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Portugal exited the bailout in May 2014, the same year that positive economic growth re-appeared following three years of recession.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] The government achieved a 2.1% budget deficit in 2016 (the lowest since the restoration of democracy in 1974) and in 2017 the economy grew 2.7% (the highest growth rate since 2000).
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Although, by 2000, Portugal was still the poorest country in Western Europe, it nevertheless had achieved a level of convergence with the developed economies in Central and Northern Europe which had no precedents in the previous centuries, a catching-up process which was expected to continue.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Portuguese economy grew a combined 0.8% in 2002, was in recession in 2003 (-0.9%) and grew 1.6% in 2004.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Ferreira Leite managed to keep deficit on 2.9% both in 2003 and in 2004, but through one-off and extraordinary measures.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Otherwise, the deficit would have hit the 5% mark.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Meanwhile, the first half of the 2000s also saw the end of the downward trend in the government debt to GDP ratio that marked the 1990s: the ratio rose from 53% in 2000 to 62% in 2004 (the ratio overtook the SGP's arbitrary limit of 60% in 2003).
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Socialist José Sócrates became Prime Minister in 2005; like his conservative predecessor, Sócrates tried to reduce the government's budget deficit through austerity and tax hikes.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] By then, the Portuguese economy was clearly lagging behind European partners and the 2005 budget deficit was expected to be above 6% if no extraordinary measures were used.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] In the Stability and Growth Programme for 2005–2009, the Sócrates' government proposed to let the budget deficit to be higher than 6% in 2005, but to structurally reduce it to below 3% until 2008, a plan which was accepted by the European authorities.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] A notable milepost in the crisis happened in 2005, when the Portuguese unemployment rate overtook the European average for the first time since 1986.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] In 2007, the government achieved a 2.6% budget deficit (one year before target), below the 3.0% limit allowed by the Stability and Growth Pact.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] That year, the economy grew 2.4%, the highest rate in the decade (excluding 2000).
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Nevertheless, also in 2007, the comparatively low growth rate made *The Economist* to describe Portugal as "a new sick man of Europe".
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] From 2005 to 2007, public debt was stable at a ratio of approximately 68% of the GDP.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] The Great Recession started to hit Portugal in 2008; that year the Portuguese economy did not grow (0.0%) and fell almost 3% in 2009.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Meanwhile, the government reported a 2.6% budget deficit in 2008 which rose to almost 10% in 2009.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Austerity was somewhat waned in 2008–2010, as part of the European economy recovery plan and the resurgence of Keynesianism (which called for anti-cyclic policies), but was resumed in May 2010.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Meanwhile, government debt-to-GDP ratio sharply rose from 68% in 2007 to 111% in 2011.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] In the end, Portuguese economy grew less on a per capita basis in the 2000s and early 2010s than the American economy during the Great Depression or the Japanese economy during the Lost Decade.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Despite government policies openly aimed to consolidate the Portuguese public finances, Portugal was almost always under excessive deficit procedure and government debt-to-GDP ratio rose from 50% in 2000 to 68% in 2007 and 126% in 2012.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] The causes of the stagnation are complex, as many potential causes also affect other Southern European countries and did not prevent them from growing in the 2000s, nor did prevent Portugal from growing before the early 2000s.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Economist Ferreira do Amaral points to the accession to Euro in 1999–2002, which was too strong as a currency for Portugal's economy and industry and took away from the country the ability to direct its own monetary (rise or reduce interest rates) and cambial policy (currency devaluation).
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Vítor Bento also thinks that the belonging to a currency union created numerous challenges to which the Portuguese economy was not able to adapt.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] A set of economists (including former Prime Minister and eventual President Aníbal Cavaco Silva, an economically liberal scholar and politician) points to the excessive size of the Portuguese government, whose total expenditures overtook 45% of the GDP in 2005.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Such hypothesis was eventually the basis for the austerity requested as conditionality for the 2011–2014 European Union/IMF bailout.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Meanwhile, the Social Security system was demanding increasing public spending, and the constant tax hikes in the 2000s limited the potential for growth of the Portuguese economy.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] It is noteworthy that from 2000 to 2007, taxes as share of GDP increased 1.7% in Portugal but declined 0.9% in Eurozone.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Another factor at the root of the stagnation may be that Portuguese economy faced increasing competition by Eastern European countries and China, which were economies also specialized in low wages and low-value-added goods.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] After the 2008 financial crisis, it was known in 2008–2009 that two Portuguese banks (Banco Português de Negócios (BPN) and Banco Privado Português (BPP)) had been accumulating losses for years due to bad investments, embezzlement and accounting fraud.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] In the grounds of avoiding a potentially serious financial crisis in the Portuguese economy, the Portuguese government decided to give them a bailout, eventually at a future loss to taxpayers.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] In the opening weeks of 2010, renewed anxiety about the excessive levels of debt in some EU countries and, more generally, about the health of the Euro spread from Ireland and Greece to Portugal, Spain, and Italy.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] In 2010, PIIGS and PIGS acronyms were widely used by international bond analysts, academics, and the international economic press when referring to these under performing economies.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Some senior German policy makers went as far as to say that emergency bailouts to Greece and future EU aid recipients should bring with it harsh penalties.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Robert Fishman, in the New York Times article "Portugal's Unnecessary Bailout", points out that Portugal fell victim to successive waves of speculation by pressure from bond traders, rating agencies and speculators.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] In the first quarter of 2010, before pressure from the markets, Portugal had one of the best rates of economic recovery in the EU.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] From the perspective of Portugal's industrial orders, exports, entrepreneurial innovation and high-school achievement, the country matched or even surpassed its neighbors in Western Europe.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] However, the Portuguese economy had been creating its own problems over a lengthy period of time, which came to a head with the financial crisis.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Persistent and lasting recruitment policies boosted the number of redundant public servants.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Risky credit, public debt creation, and European structural and cohesion funds were mismanaged across almost four decades.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Portugal would be persistently criticized for years to come by institutions and organizations like the OECD, the IMF and the European Union for its anti-market, labor movement-inspired labor laws and rules which promoted overstaffing and the misallocation of factors of production in general.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] In the summer of 2010, Moody's Investors Service cut Portugal's sovereign bond rating down two notches from an Aa2 to an A1 Due to spending on economic stimuli, Portugal's debt had increased sharply compared to the gross domestic product.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Moody noted that the rising debt would weigh heavily on the government's short-term finances.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] In September 2010, the XVIII Constitutional Government of Portugal announced a fresh austerity package following other Eurozone partners, through a series of tax hikes and salary cuts for public servants.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] In 2009, the deficit had been 9.4 percent, one of the highest in the Eurozone and well above the European Union's Stability and Growth Pact three percent limit.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] In November risk premiums on Portuguese bonds hit euro lifetime highs as investors and creditors worried that the country would fail to rein in its budget deficit and debt.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] The yield on the country's 10-year government bonds reached 7 percent – a level the Portuguese Finance Minister Fernando Teixeira dos Santos had previously said would require the country to seek financial help from international institutions.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Also in 2010, the country reached a record high unemployment rate of nearly 11%, a figure not seen for over two decades, while the number of public servants remained very high.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] On 23 March 2011, José Sócrates resigned following passage of a no confidence motion sponsored by all five opposition parties in parliament over spending cuts and tax increases.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] On 6 April 2011, José Sócrates, still in charge of the country, announced the requesting of an international financial rescue package to the Portuguese Republic.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] In May 2011, the European Union and the International Monetary Fund sealed a three-year €78 billion financial rescue plan for Portugal in a bid to stabilise its public finances.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] After the bailout was announced, the newly-elected Portuguese government headed by Pedro Passos Coelho managed to implement measures to improve the State's financial situation and the country started to be seen as moving on the right track.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Despite the unemployment rate has reached new highs above 15 per cent in the second quarter 2012, the country would be able to overcome the crisis and emerge stronger because the economic adjustment was producing the desirable effects on the Portuguese economy and public debt situation.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] On 6 April 2011, the resigning Prime Minister José Sócrates of the Socialist Party (PS) announced on television that the country, facing a status of bankruptcy, would request financial assistance to the IMF and the European Financial Stability Facility, like Greece and Ireland had done before.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] On 16 May 2011, the eurozone leaders officially approved a €78 billion bailout package for Portugal.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] A positive turning point in Portugal's strive to regain access to financial markets, was achieved on 3 October 2012, when the state managed to convert €3.76 billion of bonds with maturity in September 2013 (carrying a 3.10% yield) to new bonds with maturity in October 2015 (carrying a 5.12% yield).
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Before the bond exchange, the state had a total of €9.6 billion outstanding notes due in 2013, which according to the bailout plan should be renewed by the sale of new bonds on the market.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] As Portugal was already able to renew one-third of the outstanding bonds at a reasonable yield level, the market now expect the upcoming renewals in 2013 also to be conducted at reasonable yield levels.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] The bailout funding programme will run until June 2014, but at the same time require Portugal to regain a complete bond market access in September 2013.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] The recent sale of bonds with a 3-year maturity, was the first bond sale of the Portuguese state since requesting the bailout in April 2011, and the first step slowly to open up its governmental bond market again.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] Recently the ECB announced they will be ready also, to begin additional support to Portugal, with some yield-lowering bond purchases (OMTs), when the country regained complete market access.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] In the parliamentary elections of October 2015, the ruling right wing party failed to achieve an operating majority despite having won the elections by a solid margin.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] An anti-austerity post-electoral left wing coalition was formed achieving 51% of the vote and 53% of elected MPs, however, the President of Portugal at first refused to allow the left wing coalition to govern, inviting the minority right wing coalition to form a government.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] This was formed in November 2015 and lasted 11 days when it lost motion of confidence.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] The President eventually invited and asked the Socialist Party to form a government supported by 123 of 230 MPs in parliament from all parties except the former right wing coalition which broke into two parties.
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] The new government (of the Socialist Party and independents) took office in November 2015 with a parliamentary majority thanks to the support of the Left Bloc, the Green Party and the Communist Party and the abstention of the Animal Welfare Party (PAN).
[src:austerity/2010-14-portuguese-financial-crisis] In 2017, the IMF saw a 2.5 percent growth rate and an unemployment rate below 10 percent, but the European Commission expected Portugal's Government debt to reach 128.5 percent of GDP.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Legislative elections were held in France on 10 and 17 June 2012 (and on other dates for small numbers of voters outside metropolitan France) to select the members of the 14th National Assembly of the Fifth Republic, a little over a month after the presidential election run-off held on 6 May.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] All 577 single member seats in the assembly, including those representing overseas departments and territories and French residents overseas, were contested using a two-round system.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The elections came a month after the presidential election won by François Hollande of the Socialist Party.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Since 2002, legislative elections immediately follow the presidential ones.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] This was designed to limit the possibility of a cohabitation, whereby the President and their Prime Minister, backed by a parliamentary majority, would be of opposite parties.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The aim was also to give the new president and their government a "double mandate", the election of the President being followed by that of a parliamentary majority enabling him to implement his policies.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] By contrast, the Union for a Popular Movement, on the right, has repeatedly asked that the left not be given "all the powers" through this election.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The legislative elections in France are often described as the "third round" of the presidential election.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Among the 11 deputies who represent French citizens abroad, one is from Réunion, Corinne Narassiguin (PS), another has Chilean roots, Sergio Coronado (EELV) and a third one has Iranian roots, Pouria Amirshahi (PS).
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] A total of 6,603 candidates ran for the 577 seats, an average of 11 per constituency.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The law mandates that every party must have between 49 and 51% of women among its candidates, or have their public funding significantly reduced.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] "Some parties, among the richest, prefer to pay the fine" rather than comply with this rule, according to Libération.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The law also does not take electability into account, and significant numbers of women candidates run in constituencies where their party does not stand a real chance.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] French expatriates elected their own MPs for the first time – voting early, from 23 to 26 May or on 2 or 3 June for the first round and from 6 to 12 June or on 16 or 17 June for the second, depending on their location and the method by which they cast their ballot.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] If an expatriate votes via the Internet, he or she has a week to do so from 23 to 26 May.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] A postal ballot may be cast, if received by 31 May in the Americas or by 1 June in the rest of the world.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Those who prefer to vote in person in their local consulate must do so on 2 June in the Americas or 3 June in the rest of the world.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Each of the 577 constituencies elects one representative to the National Assembly, in a two-round election.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] A candidate is elected in the first round if he or she obtains an absolute majority of the vote in his or her constituency *and* the votes of at least one quarter of all registered voters in the constituency.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] If a large number of voters abstain, an absolute majority of the vote may thus not be enough, although this rarely happens.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] They may be joined by the third- or even fourth-placed candidate; the second round is open to any candidate who has obtained the votes of at least 12.5% of *registered* voters in the constituency.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Low turnouts therefore decrease the likelihood of a three-person runoff (known in France as a *triangulaire*).
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] In the second round, the candidate who obtains the most votes is elected; an absolute majority is not required.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Candidates who advance to the second round have the option of withdrawing.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Usually this happens in a *triangulaire*, where the party and/or candidate that finished third in the first round prefers to favour one of the two leading candidates.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] In the 2012 election, for example, third-placed UMP candidate Roland Chassain in the Bouches-du-Rhône's 16th constituency withdrew in order to help the National Front candidate defeat the Socialist candidate.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] In addition, the parties of the mainstream left (Socialist, Greens, Left Front, Radical Party of the Left, various smaller parties) have a long-standing agreement whereby they do not stand against one another in the second round.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] If two of them advance to the second round in the same constituency, the less-well-placed of the two automatically withdraws.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] In some cases, this means a *triangulaire* is avoided, and the left is united against a single right-wing candidate.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] In the 2012 election, for example, in the Hauts-de-Seine's 11th constituency, incumbent MP and Left Front candidate Marie-Hélène Amiable narrowly finished second (29.20%) behind Socialist candidate Julie Sommaruga (29.93%).
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Amiable withdrew, supporting Sommaruga in her runoff against New Centre candidate Jean-Loup Metton, who had finished third in the first round with enough support to advance to the second (24.15%).
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] In other cases, this rule means that only one candidate remains in the "second round".
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] In all these cases, no candidate of the right, centre or far right had reached the second round, meaning that the best-placed and sole remaining left-wing candidate was guaranteed to be elected in a one-person "runoff".
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The Constitutional Council approved in 2010 the first redistricting of electoral boundaries since 1986 to reflect France's changing demographics.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The population ratio between the most populated and least populated constituencies was reduced from 1:3.6 to 1:2.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] A study by Regards Citoyens indicated that the number of seats increased in areas held by the centre-right coalition led by then governing UMP at the expense of the Socialist-led opposition coalition.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Officially, the dual purpose of the redistricting was to ensure a more equal number of voters per constituency, but also to provide seats in the National Assembly to French citizens resident overseas.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Thirty-three constituencies were abolished, and thirty-three new ones created.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Of the latter, nineteen were in France, while the rest of the world was divided into eleven constituencies for French residents overseas.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The Socialist Party sought to obtain a parliamentary majority with which to implement its policies.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The Union for a Popular Movement officially aimed to win the election.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Its primary stated aim, however, was to obtain enough seats to prevent the left from having the 3/5ths Congress majority which would enable it to adopt constitutional reforms (such as granting the right to vote to foreign residents in local elections).
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The UMP's task was complicated by the popularity of the far-right National Front, which the polls indicated could obtain enough support to reach the second round in a large number of constituencies, thus splitting the right-wing vote.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The Left Front aimed to have a sizable group in Parliament, with which to have meaningful influence on the policies of the Socialist government.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The National Front aimed to obtain seats in the Assembly; it had none prior to the election.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] A secondary aim was to "sow chaos in the UMP" by maintaining candidates in the second round and thus causing the UMP potentially to lose seats.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The National Front's stated aim was eventually to replace the UMP as the main party of the right – though opinion polls credit the UMP with at least 209 seats, and the National Front with 8 at most, possibly none at all.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Europe Ecology – The Greens aimed to form an official parliamentary group, which requires having fifteen members in the Assembly.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] It had only three members prior to the election.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The Democratic Movement aimed to preserve its three seats, although its earlier ambitions were much higher.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Opinion polls suggest the party may disappear from the Assembly completely, and is unlikely to obtain any additional seats.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] In all, twelve parties or alliances stood more than a hundred candidates.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The Socialist Party had 459 candidates, and endorsed candidates of allied parties in other constituencies.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The UMP had 501 candidates, and endorsed candidates of allied parties (most notably the New Centre) in 69 other constituencies.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Marine Le Pen's "Marine Blue Gathering" had 571 candidates, and was thus present in all but six constituencies.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Most of these candidates were members of the National Front; others were from small, allied extreme right parties.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] François Bayrou's "Centre for France" alliance had 340 candidates, most of whom were members of the Democratic Movement.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] In such cases, the Socialists would support the UMP candidate as part of a "republican front" against the far right.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The UMP, by contrast, refrained from saying it would withdraw and support a Socialist candidate in those same circumstances.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Instead, 64% of UMP voters said they would favour an alliance between their own party and the extreme right for the legislative election.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Leading figures of the UMP rejected the possibility.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Chantal Jouanno said she was worried it might be under consideration, leading party leader Jean-François Copé to assure her publicly "there will never be an alliance with the National Front".
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The day after the first round, the UMP officially announced its position.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The party told its candidates not to withdraw if they had entered the second round in third place behind a Socialist candidate and a candidate of the National Front.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] In addition, in constituencies where the second round was a runoff between the left and the National Front, the UMP would not support either candidate.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Roland Chassain, UMP candidate in the Bouches-du-Rhône's 16th constituency, immediately disobeyed the party line, announcing he was withdrawing from the second round and supporting the National Front candidate.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] He explained that he considered himself "closer to Marine Le Pen than to the Socialist Party".
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] In the Gard's 2nd constituency, third-placed UMP candidate Etienne Mourrut also publicly considered defying party instructions and withdrawing in favour of National Front candidate Gilbert Collard.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Ultimately, he decided to comply with party instructions and remain in the race.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] On 12 June, Morano published an interview in the far right newspaper *Minute*, calling for "as large a gathering as possible of the right".
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Another UMP candidate, Jean-Paul Garraud, stated that his party and the National Front had "common beliefs", a statement which was criticised by Alain Juppé as being "in total contradiction" with the stated position of the UMP.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Martine Aubry, the leader of the Socialist Party, said that her party, by contrast, would support candidates of the right against the far right, as a "Republican principle".
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Arkilovitch, however, defied her party and refused to withdraw.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Pierre Moscovici, Socialist Minister of Finance, stated on 12 June that the UMP had lost its way and its values and no longer knew what it stood for, in response to its position on the National Front.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Later that same day, Prime Minister Jean-Marc Ayrault accused the UMP of "preparing a strategic alliance with the National Front", adding: "I think it was underway with Nicolas Sarkozy, but now the UMP really is at a turning point".
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The official campaign began, in metropolitan France, on 21 May.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] In every constituency, each candidate has a billboard outside every polling station, upon which to display a campaign poster.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Campaign material is also distributed by candidates' supporters in the streets and in letterboxes, and many campaign posters are illegally displayed in the streets.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Transmitting campaign material to voters by e-mail is, however, prohibited.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Each side distributes this time as it sees fit between its constituent parties.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Parties which are not represented in Parliament but which are standing at least 75 candidates are entitled to seven minutes of broadcast each.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Any campaigning whatsoever is forbidden on the eve of the election.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The leaflets of the candidates for the French nationals abroad (*Français établis à l'étranger*) seats were published online on the website of the Foreign Affairs Ministry.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The election was won by the left, providing the new government with an absolute parliamentary majority.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The parties of the presidential majority together have 55.97% of seats; with the Left Front providing them with supply and confidence.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Among the 577 members of the Assembly, 234 were new.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] A record number of women were elected: 155 (26.86%).
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Wallis and Futuna's single constituency had the highest turnout of any French electorate during the first round on 10 June, with 78% voter participation.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The Socialist Party (along with a small number of affiliated miscellaneous left candidates) obtained 300 seats, an absolute majority.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Favoured by electoral alliances with the Socialist Party, its close allies, the Radical Party of the Left and the Citizen and Republican Movement, obtained respectively 13 and 2 seats, for a total of 315.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] This meant that the Socialists could govern without having to rely on the support of other left-wing parties – the Greens, or the Left Front.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Europe Ecology – The Greens (EELV), part of the government and of the presidential majority, also benefited from an electoral alliance with the Socialists, increasing its number of seats from just 4 to 18.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] (They immediately lost one, however, as EELV leader Cécile Duflot had to relinquish her seat in order to stay in government, and her seat went to her Socialist running mate.) This enabled the Greens to form an official parliamentary group.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] They become the third biggest party in the Assembly.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The Left Front, which decided to stand alone after electoral alliance negotiations with the Socialists broke down, lost half its seats (from 19 down to 10), despite a substantial increase in the number of votes its received.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The Union for a Popular Movement (and affiliated miscellaneous right candidates), now the main opposition party, lost 112 seats, and several of its prominent members were defeated.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] In particular, 20 of the 41 members of the "Popular Right" (hard right) faction of the party standing for re-election lost their seats – most notably, Eric Raoult and Maryse Joissains-Masini.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Immediately after the defeat, leading members of the party called for a rethink of its positioning and a reassertion of its values.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Alain Juppé stated that the UMP should stand clear on its incompatibility with the National Front; François Baroin and Jean-Pierre Raffarin expressed the same view, adding that the UMP's strong "drift to the right" and increasing proximity with the ideas of the far right had been a mistake.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Party leader Jean-François Copé, however, replied that he disagreed with these views.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The Democratic Movement (MoDem) lost its leader, François Bayrou, beaten in his own constituency by his Socialist challenger.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The party's membership in the Assembly fell from 3 to 2: Jean Lassalle (re-elected in the Pyrénées-Atlantiques) and Thierry Robert (who gained a seat from the UMP in La Réunion).
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] (In Mayotte, incumbent MoDem MP Abdoulatifou Aly was eliminated with a crushingly low score in the first round.) Bayrou's defeat was seen as a potentially crippling blow not just for his own career, but for the party which he had founded, and for the centre in French politics more generally.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] All the more so as the two centre-right parties, the New Centre and the Radical Party, both lost seats, despite an electoral alliance with the UMP.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The New Centre's representation in the Assembly fell from 25 members to 14, meaning that it would no longer be recognised as a parliamentary group in itself.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The Radical Party obtained just 9 seats.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The far right obtained representatives in the Assembly for the first time since the 1997 election.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Marine Le Pen's lawyer Gilbert Collard, who is not a member of the National Front but was endorsed by it, was also elected, giving the party two seats (for the first time in twenty-four years).
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] In addition, a former member of the National Front and Movement for France, and now independent far right politician, Jacques Bompard, was elected in a constituency neighbouring Maréchal-Le Pen's, in the Vaucluse.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] In overseas departments and territories, several local parties gained or maintained representation.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The Guianese Socialist Party won a seat, returning to the Assembly for the first time since 1993.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Its MP, Gabriel Serville, was initially to sit with the Socialists, before opting to sit with the Left Front.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The Martinican Independence Movement obtained two seats (up one from the previous election).
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Boinali Said, leader of the miscellaneous left "Movement against the high cost of living", won one of the two available seats in Mayotte.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] In New Caledonia, both seats were won by the centre-right, anti-independence Caledonia Together party, which gained them from the UMP.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] In French Polynesia, the conservative, pro-autonomy but anti-independence Tahoeraʻa Huiraatira won all three seats.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] The far left parties, as well as the Pirate Party and the small environmentalist parties, failed to reach the second round in any constituency.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Based on notional party affiliation on dissolution after redistricting, regardless of party affiliation on previous election.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Based on notional distribution of seats before dissolution and after the 2010 redistricting, 149 seats switched party (26% of the National Assembly, more than in any of the three previous elections).
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] 8 seats switched from the left to the right, 9 from the extreme-left to the left, 119 from the right to the left, 3 from the right to the extreme-right, 3 from the right to the extreme-left, 2 from Modem to the left, 1 from the right to Modem.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Four seats switched party within the left (two from PS to PRG, one from PRG to PS, one from PS to EELV) as a result of coalition agreements.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] It is not compulsory in France for a government minister to obtain an electoral mandate, but ministers usually do seek the legitimacy it implies.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] As no person may simultaneously be a member of the executive and the legislature, any government minister elected to Parliament must immediately resign from their newly obtained seat in the Assembly, in order to remain a minister.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Their running mate then takes their seat, and holds it until and unless they cease to be a minister, whereupon they revert to being a member of the Assembly.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Prior to the 2012 election, new Prime Minister Jean-Marc Ayrault ruled that any minister who stood in the election and was beaten would have to resign from government.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Two ministers, Najat Vallaud-Belkacem and Christiane Taubira, opted to withdraw their candidacies in their respective constituencies.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] Twenty-five ministers (including Ayrault) did decide to stand, while the remaining eight had never expressed an intention to do so.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p01] All government ministers standing as candidates were elected or re-elected, and were thus able to remain in government.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] These constituencies attracted particular media interest, due to the presence of a notable candidate facing for example unexpected difficulties, or on the contrary an unexpectedly easy race, or due to the prospect of a significant and meaningful change in fortune for a party.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] *Libération* published a list of "twenty-five constituencies to watch out for", with commentaries.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] France 24 identified eleven "constituencies to watch out for".
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] For the first time, two major candidates from the presidential election stood in the same constituency for the legislative election.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] Jean-Luc Mélenchon (Left Front) and Marine Le Pen (National Front) are both standing in the Pas-de-Calais's 11th constituency, centred on the town of Hénin-Beaumont.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] The incumbent MP, Odette Duriez of the Socialist Party, didn't stand for re-election; the Socialist candidate was Philippe Kemel.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] The Le Pen-Mélenchon duel attracted international media attention, including for what it revealed of attitudes and expectations in an area of northern France hit hard by deindustrialisation and unemployment.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] *The Guardian* noted that, in that regard, "Mélenchon blames what he sees as pernicious free-market capitalism and bankers; Le Pen points the finger at immigrants and Europe".
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] On the first round, Le Pen won a plurality of the vote.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] The left-wing vote was split, with the Socialist candidate Philippe Kemel receiving more votes than Mélenchon.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] All three candidates qualified for the run-off, but Mélenchon withdrew and supported Kemel for the second round.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] Kemel narrowly won the seat (retaining it for the Socialist Party) with 50.1% of the vote, defeating Marine Le Pen.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] Attention was also drawn to the Pyrénées-Atlantiques's 2nd constituency, where presidential candidate François Bayrou of the centrist Democratic Movement was hoping to retain his seat.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] Bayrou had held the seat continuously since 1988, but the press raised the possibility that he might this time be beaten.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] Until 2002, the mainstream right had not stood a candidate against him, and in 2007 the candidate of the Union for a Popular Movement had withdrawn in his favour in the second round.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] Following Bayrou's personal endorsement of François Hollande for the second round of the 2012 presidential election, however, the UMP maintained a candidate against him.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] He also had to contend with a Socialist opponent, despite there having been talk in the Socialist Party of not standing a candidate in his constituency, as a gesture of acknowledgment for his endorsement of Hollande.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] Bayrou was defeated, with the seat going to Socialist candidate Nathalie Chabanne.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] In Charente-Maritime's 1st constituency, no candidate of the right, centre or far right reached the second round.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] The second round was between Ségolène Royal, the Socialist Party's candidate to the 2007 presidential election (who obtained 32.03% in the first round) and a dissident Socialist, Olivier Falorni (28.91%).
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] Falorni won the seat, defeating Royal by a comfortable margin.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] In well-off Paris's 4th constituency, the opposite situation arose: the two candidates qualified for the second round were both from the right: Bernard Debré for the UMP (45.07% in the first round), and Brigitte Kuster, a UMP dissident (23.01%).
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] Immediately after the first round, however, Kuster withdrew.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] There was a second round nonetheless, but with only one candidate, who needed simply to receive one vote in order to be elected.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] This configuration also happened in several constituencies on the left (see subsection "The two-round electoral system", below).
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] The Hauts-de-Seine's 9th constituency, traditionally a very safe seat for the right, raised unexpected difficulties for UMP candidate and former Minister of the Interior Claude Guéant.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] A dissident member of the UMP, Thierry Solere, contested his legitimacy, stood against him, and reached the second round, precipitating a three-way runoff between two candidates of the right and one of the left.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] Solere narrowly won the seat, obtaining votes from the left given Gueant's unpopularity on that side.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] The total share of the vote for left-wing candidates was 28%, in the first round, plus 4% for the Modem candidate.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] This constituency drew attention due to the behaviour and situation of UMP candidate Nadine Morano, who had been Minister for Professional Training in François Fillon's government from 2010 to 2012.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] She defined her common values with far right voters as including "control over immigration, refusing to give foreigners the right to vote" and "the protection of our borders".
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] Her situation made headlines again when humorist Gérald Dahan phoned her, pretending to be National Front vice-president Louis Aliot, and recorded her expressing her sympathy and closeness to the National Front.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] François Fillon publicly rebuked her for not having immediately hung up, saying "we don't talk to the leaders of the National Front.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] Morano hit back, telling him she was a "free politician".
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] Morano, the incumbent, lost her seat to Socialist candidate Dominique Potier by a 10% margin.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] Marie-Arlette Carlotti, junior Minister for the Disabled, stood in this constituency against the UMP incumbent Renaud Muselier, who had held the seat since 1993.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] On paper, media reported that, of all the twenty-six ministers standing in the legislative elections, she seemed the least likely to win her constituency.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] Had she lost, she would have had to resign from the government.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] She was elected with 51.8%, a result which was also described as having a significant impact on local politics in Marseille.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] As minister, she would not be able to sit in Parliament; as long as she stays in the government, her seat goes to her running mate, Avi Assouly, locally famous as a former radio football presenter.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] In addition to Marine Le Pen, Jean-Luc Mélenchon and François Bayrou, three candidates from the presidential election were standing in this legislative election.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] Nicolas Dupont-Aignan (Arise the Republic) finished first in the first round in Essonne's 8th constituency, with 42.82% of the vote, heading into a runoff with Socialist candidate Aude Bristot (30.2%), and eliminating UMP candidate Laurent Béteille (9.52%).
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] In the Gironde's 5th constituency, Philippe Poutou (New Anticapitalist Party) finished eighth and was thus eliminated in the first round, receiving just 2.12% of the vote.
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] In Seine-Saint-Denis's 6th constituency, Nathalie Arthaud (Workers' Struggle) finished sixth with 2.47%, far behind the Socialist incumbent and former Minister for Social Affairs Élisabeth Guigou (46.12%) and the director of *l'Humanité*, Patrick Le Hyaric, standing for the Left Front (17.33%).
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] *"Les dates de la présidentielle 2012 fixées".
[src:austerity/2012-french-legislative-election-p02] Jean-Claude Zarka, *Le Président de la Ve République*, Ellipses Marketing, 2007, (ISBN 978-2729831868), p.
